We invite you to join me and authors Rachel Page, Dina Dechmann, Teague O‚ÄôMara and Marco Tschapka, for a public webinar on Wed Dec 13 at 10am Panam√° time. Together, the five of us will discuss our newly published book, BAT ISLAND, taking you on a photographic journey to the rainforests of Barro Colorado Island, Panam√°, to meet the 76 species of bats that occupy this small space, and learn about their stunning natural history, physiology, evolution, sensory adaptations, foraging behavior, and social systems.
 
Join us on zoom at http://www.stri.si.edu/batisland

After years of anticipation, we're thrilled to present our bat book: ‚ÄòBAT ISLAND‚Äô, a tribute to our dear friend, Dr. Eli Kalko. Her visionary work in bat research set a remarkable course for many careers. Collaborating with exceptional authors - Dr. Rachel Page from STRI (Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute) @smithssonianbatlab, Dr. Dina Dechmann @DechmannLab (Max Planck Institute of Animal Behavior) @mpi_animalbehav , Dr. Marco Tschapka from the University of Ulm, and Dr. Teague O'Mara from Bat Conservation International - has been an incredible journey spanning two decades.

Our friendship with Eli and our shared passion for bats inspired this project. Over the last two decades, I've had the privilege of photographing the phenomenal and mysterious night flyers that continue to intrigue and inspire us.

The release of ‚ÄòBAT ISLAND‚Äô marks a milestone, sharing the captivating natural history, ecological insights, and social behavior of Barro Colorado Island's bats.

Published by Insight Editions, with authors from the Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute @smithsonianpanama, this book is an homage and testament to the profound legacy of Eli Kalko, and the impact she has had on tropical bat biology.

ü¶á Looking for the perfect Christmas gift? Look no further! üéÅ 'BAT ISLAND‚Äô is a treasure trove that captures the essence of these night flying wonders. With 160 pages of stunning imagery, BAT ISLAND delves into the captivating lives, diverse foraging habits, roosting secrets, and the fascinating social systems of Neotropical bats.

Ideal for both bat enthusiasts and inquisitive families, this book is more than just pages‚Äîit's an immersive experience into the lives of a remarkable group of animals. Whether exploring their nocturnal adventures or learning about their ecological importance, BAT ISLAND is an ideal gift to inspire awe and appreciation for the wonders of nature. Grab your copy now and gift the magic of bat exploration this holiday season! üåüü¶áüéÑ

Sharing a few more images of this remarkable moment when I encountered a bonobo with a young mongoose. 

I took all these images over about an hour as I watched this individual carry and play with a little mongoose, deep in the tropical forests of Democratic Republic of Congo. 

Big thanks to Dr. Barbara Fruth (Max-Planck Institute for Animal Behavior) and the team of the LuiKotale Bonobo Project for making these encounters possible. Follow me @christianziegler for more wildlife and nature photography!

Back from a very nice vacation, and I'm excited to share more Bonobo moments, starting with this incredible mongoose scene!

I am honored to have won the portrait category in 'Nature in focus' with this image ‚Äì thank you all for your support, especially the jury !

During my adventures near LuiKotale field station in the Democratic Republic of Congo I had a remarkable encounter. I witnessed a young male Bonobo tenderly petting a small mongoose.

This fascinating moment continued as he carefully held the mongoose while enjoying fruit in a nearby tree with the rest of his group.

However, this bond may not be as innocent as it seems. Bonobos occasionally include meat in their diet, and it's likely this young mongoose was caught when its mother was hunted by the group.

Big thanks to Dr. Barbara Fruth (Max-Planck Institute for Animal Behavior) and the team of the LuiKotale Bonobo Project for making these encounters possible. Follow me @christianziegler for more wildlife and nature photography!

time for a story. I wanted to create with Inja for a long time. she‚Äôs an actress that moved to LA from Slovenia. super down to earth and fun to chat with, but also crazy expressive and emotional in front of the camera. an absolute dream to work with. she has so much energy and personality that you hardly have to direct, if at all. 

we got coffee way back when. for one reason or another, our schedules never lined up. finally, a couple years later we ended up dialing in a shoot. an adventure, rather. 

we snuck our way into this big historic apartment complex downtown LA. once we reached the top floor, we climbed out the window at the end of the hallway onto the fire escape. the first photo from the set is there. from there, the ladder to the top of the roof was really sketchy. it went up the side of the building about 20 feet, mind you we are 20 stories up. suddenly, something fell from her pocket... a neckless. I could hear it slipping through all the cracks of the metal escape. I asked her if it was valuable. her response, ‚Äúit was silver. my mother gave it to me. it‚Äôs ok though.‚Äù we kept climbing. 

read the rest of the story and see the full set with 50 photos and a whole lot of mood - uncensored on patreon.

My story about skiing in Caucasus Mountains in Georgia is live today on @natgeo! I am thrilled to finally share this series that I worked on last year. Traveling to Ushguli, which is protected by UNESCO, has been on my bucket list for a long time, and it's one of those timeless places you can't help but return to. Huge thanks to the amazing assistance of @shako_margiani and @maticek. 

Ushguli is considered the highest permanently inhabited point in Europe. According to the publicist Besarion Nizharadze, the name Ushguli, as a toponym, originates from 'fearless heart'. Thanks for great editing to photo editor @maurafriedman @natgeo. 

Please follow the link in my profile to read the story on @natgeo. I'll be sharing more from this trip in the coming days, so stay tuned.
#natgeo #skitouring #georgia #svaneti #ushguli #leica #leicaSL

The Western Balkans region is home to some of Europe‚Äôs last free-flowing rivers. There is a growing movement of people who are fighting to protect these unique ecosystems for generations to come. We were given the task to produce 8 short films about river champions and guardians, from scientists to locals who are trying to protect rivers in the Balkans.

I am honored to serve as a nominator for the LOBA 2024 once again. The Leica Oskar Barnack Award is one of the most important photography awards, and I will never forget when I received this  recognition in 2013. We are actively seeking bodies of work centered around the theme of the relationship between humans and their environment.

If you believe you have a compelling and relevant series, please feel free to send me an email at ciril@tentfilm.com, including your work and an artistic statement. Additionally, you are welcome to tag someone whom you believe deserves this recognition. 

Attached are some photos from my LOBA-winning series 'Waiting to Move,' captured during my expedition to Shishmaref, Sarichef Island, Alaska. The purpose of this journey was to document the effects of climate change on the lives of the InÃÉupiat people.

The Ford GT90 Concept Car 

Unveiled in 1995 to celebrate Ford's 90th anniversary and honor the iconic GT40, the Ford GT90 concept car was a bold statement of automotive innovation. It housed a potent quad-turbocharged 6.0-liter V12 engine generating up to 720 horsepower. 

It included advanced features like carbon fiber construction, traction control, and active suspension, the GT90 boasted impressive performance figures, reportedly hitting a top speed of 253 mph (407 km/h) and achieving 0-60 mph in just 3.1 seconds. Despite its acclaim, the GT90 never saw production, serving as a testament to Ford's boundary-pushing engineering and design capabilities.

Rumor has it that only one GT90 Concept Car was ever made, and it currently resides at the Hajek Motorsports Museum in Ames, Oklahoma.

One of the most exciting shoots I did last year was working with the @eastafricanreptiles & Taylor Ashe Antivenom center in Watamu, Kenya to photograph spitting cobras. This particular snake is a Red Spitting Cobra (Naja pallida). Photographing these snakes is a challenge because they are not only highly venomous but they can be very aggressive/defensive as well. I had to wear a full face shield, which allowed me to avoid getting any of the venom they spit in my eyes, nose or ears.

Snakes are sadly often misunderstood and killed on sight no matter the circumstance, which is horrible because they are such a vital part of the eco systems we all live in. Organizations like East Africa Reptile's focus much of their attention not only on education and safety,  but in helping to safely remove snakes from people's homes and properties around Kenya, further increasing their chances of survival.

Last September I found myself wandering around the deserts of Dubai in search of the Horned Arabian Viper. Unfortunately for me, it was the wrong time of year as they tend to love the hot desert nights. We did however find a number of these Saw Scaled Vipers (Echis Carinatus). These beautiful snakes are easily the most deadly snake in the UAE, accounting for more snake bites per year than all other snakes combined. They can be aggressive, have a quick strike and a very powerful venom.

Thanks to @wildlifewithnitin for showing me around! Can't wait for the next adventure!

Climbing brings us together.  Once you challenge yourself with gravity and share this experience with your friends something changes. It's the international language of belaying and spotting. It's the same everywhere. You have to trust someone to achieve your goals. 

@memphisroxclimbing has been a flywheel for the good that climbing brings. Built in the shell of a supermarket with a state of the facility, Rox is bringing gym climbing and outdoor experiences to South Memphis.

With a pay as one can model, the gym is open to everyone. Climbing as I was introduced to it was free. The cliffs were at  end of the road and my dad and his buddies had the gear and knowledge. I still recall the moment when climbing and being outdoors latched on. It's that same emotion that we see with the people we welcome to the crag, mountain and gym. Let's keep that going! 

The freedom that climbing brings comes at a cost. The facility and staff are monthly obligations. In business, as in climbing, the unexpected happens. In this case a burst water pipe needs immediate attention. To keep Rox a safe place (it's a polling station, health care facility and restaurant) the security team needs immediate funding. Going without costs the program more. 

Rox has been a part of my life for the past six years. I've made new friends, shared backcountry experience & knowledge while climbing outdoors and learned from each other on how to address the challenges of race in the United States. 

If you believe in the mission of @memphisroxclimbing please consider a donation. It will be put to good use. If you have the chance to visit Memphis, stop by the gym. You'll find family by the time you have warmed up.

30 years ago today,  the last day of the year,  @johnmiddendorf4 and I climbed Cerro Torre, Patagonia via the Compressor Route. (South East Ridge) Established in 1970 by Cesare Maestri with a gasoline powered drill, the controversial route sported a stack of bolts and was the quick way to the top. 

John and I enjoyed the climb,  yet these was something amiss. The wildness of this peak was sacrificed for human ego. Maestri, making up for his fanciful ascent of 1959, bolted the peak into submission. 
 
In 2012 the late Hayden Kennedy and 
@jason_kruk removed the bolts, giving the mountain its power back and creating controversy.

If Cerro Torre is a peak that you are interested in please listen to @climbinggold. The recent season includes the Maestri Mystery with insight from @kellycordes, author of "The Tower", the definitive book on this subject.

In reviewing my journal from 30 years ago I reflect on how climbing has changed. Even if we have better weather  forecasts and lighter & stronger gear, the sense of self discovery one gets from a proper Patagonian beat down still remains. This primal connection to living is as real as it gets. 

First photo of the Cerro Torro group from the summit of Chalten by Galen Rowell.

Kyle Allen Rott 1987 - 2023 
On  November  25th we lost Kyle in a fall in Hyalite Canyon, Montana. My heart goes out to his mother and sister and the South Dakota family of this fine man.  For his friends the loss is immediate. The years of being together,  weaving the fabric of friendship through shared experiences are gone.

Kyle was a climber. Once he realized that the pursuit of gravity was his life's calling,  he lived with a singular purpose. "Let's go climb."

As someone close to Kyle, his "uncle" by age and knowing him with our family, his loss is another weight on the scale of "is it worth it".

Many of my close friends are introverts. In school we found each other and climbing self selected us. Kyle and I climbed together for 15 years - most of the time hiking the folds of Southwest Montana looking for the cliffs and drips that sustain us. In between climbs he helped out by housesitting for the climbing community. For those of that trusted Kyle without houses and animals - you know how conscientious he was.  Kyle's humble approach to life - not entertaining anything superfluous - was reflected by living in his truck.  Which made housesitting a good balance. 

While Kyle was quiet and shy in a room of his peers, there was this friendly side that Kyle shared with people in life. More than once he would carefully explain the gadgets needed to climb to curious people on the trail. This translated well to the guiding he did with Montana Alpine Guides and the Mountain School in Yosemite. 

At our service for Kyle we wrote in a small book for his mother and family. His worldly possessions, kept tidy in a Livingston storage locker, spread out over a picnic table, passed to his friends. They will cherish his memory and then ply the seas of gravity, risking it all for the moment. For his age peers, dealing with non sequential death, many for the first time, left adrift questioning and bonding closer with those that stand. I was there. And now 30 years later as an elder, with culpability and responsibility.

We love you Kyle for energy you brought to our climbing adventures. 

We love you for the reminder to live calm. 

Photos @petetapley

Big love to this guy, my dear dear friend Reinaldo Marcus Green for his new film One Love @onelovemovie out in theaters now. I don‚Äôt know how many times I‚Äôve talked about the importance of lighting throughout my career. Too many. Which is it‚Äôs so funny that Rei and I met in Lamps Plus on some random Tuesday (that‚Äôs Rei‚Äôs review on the last slide)

Biopics are notoriously hard films to make, especially when the person depicted is still fresh in our memory. Covering an entire life and weaving it all together is an incredibly difficult task. It‚Äôs arguable that Bob Marley is the most globally recognizable musician in the world. His music is pervasive and I‚Äôve heard it everywhere I‚Äôve traveled, from an international science station in Antarctica to a boat in the Russian Arctic to a tea house in Tibet. Few contemporary artists have such a fingerprint and I believe his message is important now more than ever.

It‚Äôs hard to comprehend the undertaking of Rei, Kingsley Ben-Adir, Lashana Lynch @lashanalynch and everyone else involved in the film. Regardless, under his direction, the roles are transformative and played with incredible skill and care. Well done! Go have some popcorn and let the music you already know be born again.

The curb weight of the Porsche 356, the first Porsche automobile, was 1700 ‚Äì 2,296 lbs. The weight of the Porsche name is much heavier. Ferdinand ‚ÄòFerdi‚Äô Porsche, an architect by trade and the great grandson of the company‚Äôs founder Prof. Ferdinand Porsche, is now adding his fingerprint to the family‚Äôs rich motor-sports legacy.

At 30 yrs old, Ferdi defies all the seriousness and pomp of racing cars. He‚Äôs affable, warm, and almost boyish in his excitement. To put it bluntly, he‚Äôs ‚Äòcool‚Äô without effort, working hard to invite the next generation into the motorsports world.

 On February 24, Ferdi‚Äôs F.A.T. International held its first ice race in Zell am See, Austria, and has followed it up in Aspen, Colorado. Over the past two days on an icy track in Carbondale, the race has included models from the @aetherapparel Half11 (half Porsche, half F1) to the Rivian R1T, to a host of various Mobil 1 cars tearing around corners, over-steering, under-steering, and generally bringing joy as they spit rooster tails of snow from their tires. 

I watch as an enthusiast warm his hands in the exhaust of a loud engine. He brings them to his nose, closes his eyes and inhales deeply, letting his senses coalesce into something whole and visceral. Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // In the wide desert of Upper Mustang, the road planes along canyon walls and dry mountainsides dotted with hundreds of unspeakably ancient human-made caves. The light plays a slow game of chase with the shadows cast by the highest mountains on the planet, now behind us. We sweep the corners wide, drawn to cliff-edges teetering above the braided Kali Gandaki River below. We don‚Äôt know where to look ‚Äì the road, the layers of tortured mountains, or the sand-castle parapets of rock and mud towering above us.
 
Instead, we watch the oncoming frame-bent jeeps as they roaring around the blind corners on bald tires. In Tsarang, the drivers share a rough kindness with us. We play snooker, a game we don‚Äôt know. Cory tries and fails to find a tutorial on YouTube. Nursing warm cans of beer, we realize the drivers don‚Äôt know how to play either.
 
The evening passes in one long, impossible game of scratches and flubs until the young man running the hall flicks the light switch and kicks us out into the cold, thin air of a star-streaked night.  @vacheronconstantin

Our hearts remain with the thousands of families that have lost loved ones in the 6.4 magnitude earthquake in West Nepal. As winter approaches, tens of thousands remain without adequate shelter or warmth. If you‚Äôd like to contribute please visit Blinknow.org - these are friends of ours working tirelessly on the ground, and every contribution matters.

We will resume our Mustang travelogue starting today to celebrate all the beauty, resiliency, and magic of Nepal in the faith that if we all work together, brighter days will come soon. // following words by @jetbutterflies Hoping for mountains, we find fog. Climbing towards Sarangkot, the city disappears behind us. Marigolds line the road that falls away into steeped terraces dotted by clusters of roughhewn homes. An hour in, we find the main highway again, paved and twisted into tight curls across the steep hillsides like a pig‚Äôs tail. Todd‚Äôs back wheel blows up, death-wobbling him across the narrow road and directly into a stable of split-open motor scooters under a corrugated tin roof held together with wire.

The mechanic opens the rear tire, and leaves the parts strewn across the shoulder of the highway. A metal-handled hammer and broken screwdriver finish the job: a blown bearing. The mechanic isn‚Äôt much of a talker. He saddles a scooter and buzzes off to somewhere while the town gathers around us, sharing stories and children and a, most proudly, new iPhone 12 ProMax.  They return with two bearings ‚Äì ‚ÄúJapan‚Äù brand. ‚ÄúBest quality‚Äù, he says.
Four hours of riding to go. @vacheronconstantin @aetherapparel

The thing about earthquakes is that they impact poor and vulnerable communities the most. Those who can‚Äôt afford to reinforce their homes, or who don‚Äôt have a surplus of resources like family, income, or grain to weather months of rebuilding and trauma.

In light of the recent 6.4 magnitude earthquake that struck Western Nepal last night - just miles from Mustang - and our hope to focus public attention on supporting relief efforts, we will postpone our travelogue until next week.

Currently, there are 150+ known deaths from the quake with many hundreds more injured and tens of thousands left without shelter as winter approaches. Please watch this space for updates on how you can help the families in Jajarkot and Rukum recover and build back better.

With love, 
Cory and Ben

Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // The highway is a perpetual a fever dream of construction and destruction. Dust, scattered pavement, clawed ridges of clay are punctuated with the idle carcasses of heavy equipment, thin herds of goats, and garish tractors bouncing between knee-deep ruts. When you don‚Äôt have any lanes, you‚Äôre always splitting lanes.
 
Six days ago, Cory did what any responsible motorcyclist would do: he watched a YouTube video titled ‚ÄúHow to Ride a Motorcycle in ONLY 1 HOUR,‚Äù which, it turns out, was only twenty minutes long. 
 
Cory then traced the backstreets of Santa Monica on a tiny caf√© racer for five days before boarding a plane for Kathmandu. Now, eight hours of riding on Nepal‚Äôs worst and busiest highway later, the sun collapses across rice paddies heavy with grain. We still have hours to go.
 
In this perpetual present, when you‚Äôre gripped, you experience the relativity of time. It slows to a game of seconds until, as if by magic, hours have passed.

I‚Äôve known Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies for over a decade. He‚Äôs a Kathmandu staple and has called Nepal home for twenty some years. He came for the mountains and stayed for the people, starting and running non-profits for pieces of the community. At his heart, he‚Äôs an artist and filmmaker. He‚Äôs also a ferocious writer. I‚Äôve been to Mustang with him before on assignment for NG. But this trip is just for us. The following posts are his words.
 
Our other companion is Todd Hoffman. He doesn‚Äôt use Instagram. He‚Äôs one of those leather-faced legends of the eighties who lived hard and fast enough to know when to leave the racetrack. Even if you hardly know him, you want him on your team. At your back. If he looks familiar, it might be from that one time he took Pepsi to task over a Harrier jump jet.

Have you ever looked back at a time in your life where you wished you had just slowed down and enjoyed it a little more? There have been many times that I wish I had been a little less preoccupied with the unnecessary nonsense that seemed to have consumed me and focused more on enjoying the present. I think back to when I was younger, I think of all the BS fad diets I tried, the stress I would put myself through to weigh less or meet some unrealistic standards for my body. I think of the things I kept wanting to change in myself and the comparisons I would make to others. 

But you know what, when I think back to those days, I don‚Äôt remember what I weighed, I don‚Äôt remember when I had visible abs or when I had a little extra padding. I remember creating memories with my family, I remember creating, travelling, meeting incredible people from all around the world and making lifelong friends. I remember all the special things that can so easily escape us on the day-to-day basis but I didn‚Äôt have a single fond memory that was associated with being restrictive or obsessive when it came to body image. 

Funnily enough the moment I decided to stop focusing on purely the aesthetic side of fitness I achieved what I wanted as a by-product of enjoying the process and getting stronger. 

If you want to start training for long term, sustainable results, check out the programs in my bio ‚ù§Ô∏è

3 Reasons your glutes aren‚Äôt going üçë

Building muscle is hard work and takes time. You have to be patient and consistent to see results. Here are some reasons you may not be seeing results and how to overcome them: 

1Ô∏è‚É£ Inadequate Training Volume or Intensity:

Issue: Building muscle requires adequate training stimulus. If you‚Äôre not training with enough intensity (upping your weights and training close to failure for at least your first compound lift) your glutes may not be receiving the necessary stimulation to grow.

Solution: Focus on increasing the intensity of your workouts by increasing the weight you‚Äôre lifting, incorporate progressive overload and include more glute-focused exercises in your routine. 

2Ô∏è‚É£ Inadequate Nutrition or Recovery:

Issue: Not fuelling your body properly and overtraining can hinder your results. 

Solution: Muscles need proper nutrition and recovery to grow. If you‚Äôre not consuming enough calories, particularly protein, your body may lack the essential building blocks for muscle growth. Additionally, inadequate rest and recovery can hinder progress. Make sure you‚Äôre getting enough quality sleep, managing stress and allowing your muscles to recover between workouts.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Not following a structured program 

Issue: Changing your workouts every session isn‚Äôt going to help you build your glutes.It can be tempting to jump on the latest glute building trend or exercise that promises to build your glutes after 1 session but the reality is that building your glutes takes time and requires you to perform the same workouts for at least 4 - 6 weeks, progressively increasing the intensity (progressive overload). 

Solution: Following a program that incorporates progressive overload and has a well structured exercise selection will help you maximise your gains.

I don‚Äôt cut or bulk and I don‚Äôt restrict myself either. There‚Äôs not much I love more than meeting interesting people and learning what makes them tick. So when @oneplus commissioned me to interview and photograph Marc Spelmann (@iamspelmann) for @VICE, I jumped at the opportunity.

You‚Äôve probably seen Marc at work ‚Äî even if you don‚Äôt know it yet ‚Äî on Britain‚Äôs Got Talent or America‚Äôs Got Talent as his alter-ego, Magician X (@iammagicianx), leading to incredible success online and off, and hundreds of millions of fans around the world.

We spent an afternoon at Marc‚Äôs home studio in London chatting about our shared love of sci-fi, special effects, cognitive psychology, and design (among his many talents, Marc is a trained illustrator and graphic designer), and of course, magic.

Marc is, unsurprisingly, a talented wordsmith, and one thing he said keeps running circles around my head in the days since our chat, as it applies to so many human endeavours: ‚ÄúAnything is possible if you put your mind to it, and you have to have that mindset because ultimately what you‚Äôre trying to create is something that should not exist.‚Äù Brilliant.

His story is as captivating as his illusions¬†‚Äî read more from our chat at the link on my profile, and check out Marc and Magician X on Instagram and YouTube for more magic.

All photos (and video) captured on the new OnePlus 12.

Whenever I‚Äôm about to head back to Vienna, I get a happy pang similar to homesickness (appropriately, there is a word in German for exactly this: ‚Äúfernweh‚Äù); a place I was planning to call home before the pandemic (and Brexit) interrupted, I‚Äôm still aiming to make it at least a part-time home one day.

Looking back on these images from February 2020 feels a bit dreamlike¬†‚Äî news outlets were buzzing about COVID-19 during my visit. I remember being surprised that there were no border restrictions upon my return to London, as the first confirmed cases in Austria had been discovered the day of my flight.

That trip was full of promise and excitement for things to come:¬†a full Spring & Summer of travel, workshops, documentary filmmaking, and commissions; a few months in Fall set aside for apartment-hunting in Vienna; years of planning, preparing, and patience all coming to fruition.

Though the last 4 years haven‚Äôt exactly played out how I imagined (ha!), each return to Vienna feels like a mini-reset back to that pre-pandemic energy and momentum.

Hope to see some of you at Wednesday‚Äôs mini-workshop and photowalk ‚Äî¬†link in the usual places ‚úåüèº

üîç leica vienna kodak retina ilford hp5 blackandwhite film analog photography

More views from Vienna, this time from October 2023 on the new Phoenix color film.

The last few years have been (mostly) good for analog photography: the new Leica M6, increased use of ECN-2 film stocks and processing, news of a new line of Pentax film cameras ‚Äî¬†while we‚Äôre also facing rising film prices and ongoing economic issues elsewhere, I‚Äôll take positive news when it comes.

When Phoenix was released, there was a certain amount of negativity about who was sent sample rolls as the launch coverage and reviews rolled out. The common complaint was that it was only sent to ‚Äúinfluencers‚Äù ‚Äî¬†not a term I love, though people with influence have always been a good strategy for getting the word out.

The implication was that if Phoenix had been sent to ‚Äúreal‚Äù photographers for testing, the images would have been better, or the reviews wouldn‚Äôt have been as favorable, etc. ‚Äî and that the generally-positive public feedback on the new film was only due to said influencers not wanting to get on Harman‚Äôs bad side.

This sort of commentary smells like jealousy, and I get it ‚Äî¬†there are a LOT of amazing photographers out there who haven‚Äôt been blessed by social media‚Äôs algorithmic deities, and it can be frustrating to see opportunities being handed to other people when you feel you could do better. However, indignance doesn‚Äôt do anyone any favors.

It‚Äôs also easy to be jaded, and say companies like @harmanphoto are making a money-grab by selling a limited edition product ‚Äî¬†though I‚Äôd wager most of the folks who made that argument happily took advantage of Black Friday deals.

Harman launched a new, niche product, and you can‚Äôt do that without promotion ‚Äî¬†if you can get the bulk of your press by sending people free product, more power to you.

So, let people be excited about new film! The world has enough darkness right now ‚Äî¬†choose to shine a light where you can.

(Continued in comments)

Heading back to Vienna next week ‚Äî one of my favorite cities ‚Äî to run another mini-workshop and photowalk with my buddy Jahan (@doyoudevelop) and the good folks at @leica_akademie_austria & @leica_camera_austria. Link in my bio + Stories, et al.

This time we‚Äôre digging into high-speed B&W film (3200ISO, pushing film, and the like), so I thought I‚Äôd share some images I‚Äôve been sitting on for a while.

In February 2020, I was in Vienna for a few weeks and brought along a camera I‚Äôd had in my collection for years but never used: a Kodak Retina 1a from 1953.

I slowly captured a single roll of HP5+ while wandering Vienna‚Äôs streets, zone focusing at f11‚Äì16, pushing the roll 1-stop (effectively turning 400ISO film into 800ISO) to keep the shutter speeds higher at those smaller apertures.

I‚Äôll share some more from this roll in a few days ‚Äî it‚Äôll be nice to revisit Vienna on high-speed B&W film nearly 4 years on üéûÔ∏è

This last tip in the current smartphone photography series seems obvious once you know it: When using devices with multiple lenses, use the exact focal length (or multiplier, e.g. 2√ó, 3√ó, etc.) to Zoom with the highest quality.

Newer devices will of course give you amazing images throughout their zoom range, but just as in the days of single-lens smartphones, cropping an image slightly will provide better quality than zooming the same amount.

White Balance (sometimes called ‚ÄúColor‚Äù or ‚ÄúTemperature‚Äù depending on your software) is a key tool when editing any image, regardless of the lighting conditions. As smart as our devices are, it‚Äôs possible for a photo to need correction if it looks different than what our eyes see ‚Äî or you may want your subject to be warmer or cooler for effect. Either way, White Balance is important to understand and use.

I‚Äôm making this on repeat at the moment, so wanted to share the recipe with you. It‚Äôs a family favourite, such a good staple and one of the easiest ways to up your veggie intake. It‚Äôs a nice one for food waste too, simply swap the veg for anything you‚Äôve got lying around at home - leeks, whole tomatoes, courgettes, leafy greens etc are all delicious additions, likewise white beans instead of chickpeas and any pasta shape instead of orecchiette (broken pieces of lasagne are fab, as is orzo). Dial the chilli up or down to taste, or simply add it at the end if you‚Äôre making this for little ones (once you‚Äôve served them) 

For the nourishing veggie broth with orecchiette, you‚Äôll need 
- 2 tablespoons olive oil
- 1 large onion, thinly sliced
- 2 carrots, halved lengthways & cut into 1cm half moons
- 2 sticks of celery, finely chopped
- 4 cloves garlic, crushed/finely chopped
- 2 bay leaves
- small handful of thyme sprigs
- 1 tablespoon tomato pur√©e
- 1 tablespoon brown rice miso paste
- 1 x 400g tin chopped tomatoes
- 1 x 400g tin chickpeas, drained
- 1¬º litre vegetable stock
- 3 servings of orecchiette (about 225g)
- large handful of basil
- pinch of dried red chilli flakes
- pinch of sea salt

1. Warm the olive oil in a large deep saucepan or casserole dish set over medium heat. Add the onion, carrots, celery, garlic, a pinch of salt and cook for 5 minutes until slightly softened.

2. Stir in the bay leaves, thyme leaves, tomato pur√©e and miso; cook for 2‚Äì3 minutes until fragrant. 

3. Next, pour in the tinned tomatoes, chickpeas and stock. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer for 10‚Äì15 minutes until the vegetables are tender. 

4. Remove the pan from the heat and use a hand blender to roughly blitz half of the soup to thicken it slightly (if you like), then return to the heat, add the pasta and cook for 8‚Äì10 minutes until al dente. 

5. Divide between bowls and scatter over the basil, chilli flakes (if using) and a drizzle of olive oil

‚ÄúHi Anna. Our brigade surrenders in captivity today. Me too. I don‚Äôt know what will happen next. I love you all.‚Äù
_____________

Waiting for Serhiy

His attempts to escape the Russian siege had failed. He and his fellow Ukrainian Marines were surrounded, dozens of miles from friendly lines. They were nearly out of food and ammunition. Some panicked, others quietly resigned themselves to what would come next.
Then, a few days later, senior sailor Sergey Hrebinyk and his comrades emerged from the sprawling Ilyich Iron and Steel works in the southern Ukrainian city of Mariupol. He quickly messaged his older sister: ‚ÄúHi Anna. Our brigade surrenders. In captivity today. I also don‚Äôt know what will happen next. I love you.‚Äù
It was April 12, 2022.

Nearly two years later, on the second anniversary of the start of Russia‚Äôs full scale invasion, Serhiy Hrebinyk, 24, remains in captivity as a prisoner of war, held somewhere in Russia. His family sits in purgatory, trapped between that day in April and the present.

The initial panicked flurry of calls to the Red Cross, the Ukrainian military and local officials subsided as official proof of life took months to come. The war dragged on, and now, like thousands of other Ukrainian families with relatives in captivity, the Hrebinyks wait.

‚ÄúLife, of course, has changed. Almost every day is filled with tears,‚Äù said Svitlana Hrebinyk, Serhiy‚Äôs mother.

Words @tmgneff Photos @dguttenfelder Editing @adamjdean for @nytimes in Sumy. Ukraine marking two years of war since the full-scale Russian invasion.

Ukrainian soldiers rested inside a destroyed building on the edge of the newly liberated but desolate village of Blahodatne. It was one of seven villages that Ukraine had retaken during the early days of the counteroffensive against Russia and just one of dozens, or hundreds that would need to be bled over if their strategy could succeed. 

This photograph is part of the @nytimes 2023 The Year In Pictures. It‚Äôs been a year of very dark days and unprecedented danger for fellow journalists in Gaza and Lebanon, Israel, Ukraine... 

Please have a look at the pictures (link in my bio) and read the words of some of the women and men who stood their ground with their cameras.

Ukrainian military manning tanks and mobile artillery (and a ‚ÄúBuhanka‚Äù) on the Kharkiv front lines.
December 2023

Everything that rises must converge.

Kyiv 11/27/23

Ukraine October 2023

Emerging from an underground bunker in a tree line, Ukrainian soldiers fired their 50+ year old Soviet-era artillery at Russian frontline infantry near Bakhmut. 

The town cleared another acre of ground and began digging fresh graves to make room for many of the 52 killed in one vicious Russian missile strike on mourners who‚Äôd gathered for a wake in the village of Hroza. 

A steady flow of injured soldiers, cared for by combat medics in this hidden Donetsk region outpost. 

Boots and bloody clothing, cut away from injured Ukrainian soldiers before evacuation from the front, were heaped in the hallway and yard at one combat medic outpost in the Kupiansk direction. 

@nytimes

Yuri, a Ukrainian villager from Hroza, wandered in the ruins. His wife Halyna died here the day before. 

A missile strike on the Ukrainian village of Hroza killed at least 52 people, including every known member of one family in the area. As much as a third of the population were killed in the attack. 

‚ÄúEverybody died,‚Äù one resident said.

Within a week I‚Äôll begin my second bicycle-tour of Norway, but first I took my family to one of my favourite hikes in our county. Even my sister‚Äôs little dog joined us for the gruelling 21km hike with an elevation gain exceeding 1300m. At the summit someone had left homemade cloudberry liqueur. To whom ever made the liqueur it was delicious!

An empty Pulpit in June is impressive, but nothing compared to the 19-year-old adventurous Dutchie we met on the rock @guus_malenstein. His original plan was to cycle from the Netherlands to Trondheim (Norway), but the moment he arrived in Denmark his bike disintegrated. Without sufficient funds to make the repairs he decided to walk instead. At the Norwegain border he told the border guards that he needed to visit his grandmother. The guards let him in.‚Å£
‚Å£
I must admit, I‚Äôm impressed by the young crazy Dutchie. You don‚Äôt meet brave people like him daily, who are on a thousand-kilometre trek alone admits a pandemic. ‚Å£

In contrast to the documentary and journalistic approaches that characterize most of my photography, my ‚Äúabandoned moments‚Äù work instead relies on intuition and my gut in order to capture images without looking through the viewfinder. Photographs from my personal project documenting Syrian refugee camps in Jordan and Iraq. After having worked in Syria over 7 trips between 1991 and 2009, once their brutal civil war exploded out of the Arab Spring, I was determined to find a way to tell the story of mental health amongst Syrian refugees. This was a story that was dear to me and I had the chance to pitch the idea to International Medical Corps. I spent two weeks in Northern Iraq and Jordan to tell this story, which was ultimately published by Time magazine.‚Å£
Throughout my career personal projects have defined my work and been the lifeblood of my working life.‚Å£

Mirror, Mirror | ‚ÄúMirror, Mirror, on the wall, who‚Äôs the fairest of them all?‚Äù This now ubiquitous English phrase came from a Disney movie, Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs.‚Å£
‚Å£
In photography, mirrors play an important role, serving as a compositional device, and as an element that makes the image more magical, dramatic, mysterious or just visually engaging. The creative use of mirrors in photography gives a poetic license to create imagery that is less obvious or straightforward, but allows for alternative ways of capturing a moment, a character and a scene. It can also be an effective way of avoiding direct contact with a subject or to render a sensitive or difficult situation without direct confrontation.‚Å£
‚Å£
These images from my archive reflect the multitude of ways mirrors serve as visual devices in photography.‚Å£
‚Å£
Captions:‚Å£
‚Å£
1. Donia Remedios, 73, who has pancreatic cancer, spends time at home with her daughter, Orlanda Hernandez Ramirez Remedios, 44, at their family compound. MEXICO 2014‚Å£
‚Å£
2. A Muslim woman is reflected in a car mirror while Christian women are seen walking down the street in Kano. NIGERIA 2013‚Å£
‚Å£
3. Backstage at the Al Fala Theatre in Lahore, actress Nida Chaudrey reflection speaks of the bawdy and racy burlesque shows for which the theater is known. Bombed in early 2009 by extremists attempting to send a message, patrons still attend regularly. The sexual entertainment attracts mostly male viewers who pack the evening shows, but occasionally couples and families also attend. PAKISTAN 2009‚Å£
‚Å£
4. Wealthy young Kuwaitis shop for jewelry at Bulgari. KUWAIT 2000‚Å£
‚Å£
5. Clouds drift in the sky over Bozeman, Montana. USA 2015‚Å£

A recent article in The Economist reported on the issue of stray cows in India and how the right‚Äôs pro-cow policies are doing little to protect the sacred animals. I‚Äôve traveled to India over 10 times on assignment and have seen with my own eyes the way cows are a part of daily life. I‚Äôve always been fascinated by the special position cows have in Hindu society. At first I thought it was unusual, but over the years and many visits I‚Äôve come to not only appreciate the beliefs around a cow‚Äôs sacredness, but also understand that virtually every part of a cow, from their feces, meat, bones, skin, urine, etc, has a value. Whether it‚Äôs using their feces for fuel or building your home, to their skin for clothing and protection, it‚Äôs incredible what overall value, at least from a human‚Äôs perspective of dominion over the natural world, represents. No wonder cows are considered sacred. ‚Å£
‚Å£
But I‚Äôve also seen the downside of this reverence, where cows are left to wander and get sick and literally die on the streets. The ruling conservative party, BJP, has passed several ‚Äúpro-cow‚Äù policies like a ban on cow slaughter, but that has only led to the proliferation of stray cows, now numbering over 5 million. 

Abandoned, they often feed on plastic bags and other garbage, and can cause car crashes and destroy crops. One thing is certain ‚Äì the current situation is untenable and more must be done to protect India‚Äôs stray cows.‚Å£
‚Å£

‚Å£
From the romantic to the traumatic, how do two people hold together and why or what brings them together. In some sense, it‚Äôs the most desired and natural relationship humans strive to attain, yet two people can be brought together for reasons or circumstances that are not positive or romantic or comforting.
‚Å£
There have been couples I‚Äôve met in my lifetime, and I imagine anyone reading this has experienced the same thing, who are so perfectly matched, that if they were to ever break up you‚Äôd think the world was coming to an end. The qualities that I see exemplifying coupling are trust, care, being able to listen and make space for a mate‚Äôs feelings and thoughts, and of course being able to laugh with each other. Yet, some people couple out of desperation, need, economics, lust and social pressures.‚Å£

‚ÄúLight Walker‚Äù

A self portrait series from just a few weeks ago in Deadvlei, Namibia.  A place I‚Äôve dreamed of visiting for a decade‚Ä¶ and yet being there in person, walking barefoot across the dead marsh under these 600-900 year old skeleton trees, was such a surreal experience unlike what I imagined it would be.  It‚Äôs strange to walk through a place that feels so long dead and forgotten - yet still full of life and wonder.

I originally had an entirely different series of images in my mind for here, involving a couple of different colourful dresses (red and gold) and dance poses mimicking and flowing with these trees‚Ä¶ but when I arrived here, just as the sun rose and lit up my surroundings and as I walked over the last sand dune to see the dead pan valley floor below, all those earlier visions I had simply vanished. Thankfully, tucked away in the bottom of my backpack under my camera gear and red/gold dresses (anyone else cram dresses and chocolate into their backpack as a general hiking norm?), I had also this white dress as a back-up‚Ä¶ and I was so glad I brought it, because all I could actually envision in person here was a balance of death and life, light and dark, a dream walking through decay. 

And so that‚Äôs how I spent the next 3 hours - walking and running around barefoot, feeling connection, contrast and awe, and creating this new series as it came to me. ü§ç What a surreal place.

‚ÄúThe Heart of Ancient Earth‚Äù

3/100 of my year-long self portrait project. üíô

This was taken at 2am in Iceland - the only time I‚Äôve ever seen this location, Reynisfjara beach, completely empty of visitors.  The basalt columns eerily rose out of the midsummer night fog, and everything was still and silent, even the waves in the ocean right next to these columns - a calm rarity I‚Äôve never seen here before. 

This was my first night ever being high enough in the north to experience no complete darkness, even at 2am.  The light was soft and blue, and the settings and emotions felt in this place all came together to inspire this self portrait‚Ä¶ a moment of connection with the ancient earth. üíô

‚ÄúThe Essence of Lightness‚Äù

A self portrait taken at midnight in Iceland last summer (the time of endless light!). üíô

So far every morning this year I‚Äôve been deep diving into my journal, writing out and contemplating what it would be like to live lighter.  To cultivate an ease and lightness in my mind, to be less busy, to be more trusting in the unknown future.  To play more, and let my inner child lead me romping through the woodlands and meadows, inspired by my imagination. 

I thought I‚Äôd share this lil blurb I brain-barfed out onto the pages this morning. ü§ì‚¨áÔ∏è

‚ÄúThis year I want to let go of pressure.  Both the pressure I put on myself, and the pressure the societal world puts on us all. 

I let go of the pressure to be perfect. The pressure to look a certain way. The pressure to post every day. I let go of the pressure I put on myself to create better and better images, videos and paintings.

This year I embrace lightness. I celebrate imperfection, because when I allow myself and my creations to be made imperfectly with my mind open, it creates space for a world of new ideas, opportunities and surprise happenings I never would have dreamed up myself in my ‚Äúperfect world‚Äù.

This year I let my true essence take the seat of my mind and being. I take time to intentionally practice dwelling in my truest state - the state of complete trust, leading to peace and joyful lightness, where I feel the most myself. 

This year I allow myself to live. Not by someone else‚Äôs standards, and not by the standards I once thought I should hold over myself. 

I live by listening. I listen intently to what brings me a sense of joy, rightness and lightness. I listen to what I can give - what I can naturally offer and help bring out in others.

I live by being kind. I live in gratitude for the freedom I‚Äôm so, so, so incredibly fortunate to have access to.

I allow this freedom to be protected, nurtured and loved, to not let this gift be taken for granted or hijacked by the endless hustling pressures of the world.

This year I embrace lightness. I put my heart first, and I let love, trust and wonder lead the way down this path of life. This one chance we have to truly live.‚Äù ü§ç

Spinach and ricotta shells üòã

This recipe is one of my favourite pasta dishes, so easy to make and a great one for entertaining too ü§åüèº

Ingredients:‚Ä®- 250g ricotta‚Ä®- 3 tbsp lemon juice‚Ä®- 100g chopped spinach‚Ä®- 1 tbsp minced garlic‚Ä®- 1 tsp salt‚Ä®- cracked pepper, to taste‚Ä®- 700g passata‚Ä®- handful of fresh basil leaves‚Ä®- 12 pasta shells‚Ä®- sprinkle of parmesan‚Ä®- 1 tbsp pine nuts

Method:
1. Preheat the oven to 180¬∞C fan-forced and place a large pot of water to boil over the stove, on high heat.
2. Once water is boiled, add the pasta shells to the pot. Cook as per packet instructions, ensuring not to overcook. Then, drain and rinse with cold water.
3. Add passata, fresh basil leaves, 1/2 tsp salt and pepper to a 30cm x 20cm baking dish and mix, spreading evenly.
4. Add ricotta, lemon, spinach, garlic, 1/2 tsp salt and pepper to a bowl and mix well to combine.
5. One-by-one, spoon approx 2 tbsp of the ricotta mixture into each shell and place into the baking dish. Repeat until shells and ricotta mixture are all used up.
6. Sprinkle with parmesan and pine nuts, and place into the oven to bake for 15-20 minutes, or until pine nuts and pasta shells begin to brown.
7. Serve hot & enjoy!

#vegetarian #vegetarianrecipe #pastarecipe #easyrecipe

Creamy tomato burrata pasta üçÖ

This pasta dish is such a great, simple meal for the Summertime! It‚Äôs super easy to make and absolutely delicious, hope you enjoy üòã

(Serves two)

Ingredients:‚Ä®- 2 tbsp butter‚Ä®- 1 garlic clove, minced‚Ä®- 1 whole chilli, diced‚Ä®- 250g cherry tomatoes‚Ä®- 2 tbsp tomato paste‚Ä®- 1 cup thickened cream‚Ä®- 250g pasta, cooked al dente‚Ä®- 150g burrata‚Ä®- fresh basil leaves, to serve‚Ä®- salt and pepper, to taste

Method:‚Ä®1. Cook your pasta and prepare garlic and chilli‚Ä®2. Place a large frying pan over medium-high heat on the stove, add butter and melt‚Ä®3. Add pre-cooked pasta and mix well with the sauce‚Ä®7. Tear burrata into chunks and pick fresh basil leaves. Add to the pasta‚Ä®8. Enjoy!

A super easy 5 minute choc self-saucing pudding!

Pudding:‚Ä®- 3 tbsp self raising flour‚Ä®- 3 tbsp coconut sugar‚Ä®- 1 + 1/2 tbsp cacao powder‚Ä®- 3 tbsp soy milk‚Ä®- 1/2 tsp vanilla extract‚Ä®- 2 tbsp olive oil

Sauce:‚Ä®- Pinch of salt‚Ä®- 3 tbsp boiling water‚Ä®- 1 tsp cacao powder‚Ä®- 1 tbsp coconut sugar

Method:

Serves 2

Ingredients:‚Ä®- 400g can chopped tomatoes‚Ä®- 2 tbsp finely diced red onion‚Ä®- 2 garlic cloves, crushed‚Ä®- 1/4 tsp cayenne pepper (or to taste)‚Ä®- 1 tsp smoked paprika‚Ä®- 1/2 tsp ground cumin‚Ä®- 1/2 tsp sea salt‚Ä®- black pepper, to taste‚Ä®- 2 eggs‚Ä®- 2 cubes feta‚Ä®- 2 tsp olive oil‚Ä®- parsley, to serve‚Ä®- bread, to serve‚Ä®‚Ä®Method:‚Ä®1. This delicious, creamy ramen is perfect in the cooler months üçú Packed full of veggies and tofu for protein, it‚Äôs also super easy to make üå± This recipe is on page 70 of my 3rd cookbook, Simple Vegan Kitchen. Enjoy!

Serves 2 - 4

Ingredients:
1 tbsp oil, any kind for frying
1 cup/100 g finely sliced shiitake mushrooms
1 x 400g can of corn, drained
1 pak choy bunch, roughly chopped
2 spring onions, finely sliced
300g soft tofu, drained and cut into 1-2cm cubes
200g ramen noodles (GF rice noodle optional)
1 nori sheet, shredded
Broth:
1 veggie stock cube
1.5 tbsp miso paste
1 tbsp soy sauce
2.5 cup oat milk (GF sub for cashew/soy milk, I used Vitasoy oat milk)
1.5 cup boiling water
1 tbsp sesame oil
Optional
Sriracha 
Japanese seasoning 

Method:
1. Place a large pot over medium - high heat, add oil, once hot, add mushrooms and fry for 2 minutes, strirring occasionally. Add corn and white portion of spring onion. Fry for further 2 minutes.
2. Place another large pot filled with water over high heat, bring water to the boil and cook noodles as per packet instruction.
3. Slice pak choy into quarters and fry over medium heat, until lightly crispy. Set to the side.
4. Crumble the vegetable stock cube into a bowl with the boiling water, add miso paste and stir to dissolve, add to the pot of vegetables, along with the oat milk and soy sauce, bring to the boil and then remove from heat. Stir in sesame oil.
5. Drain noodles and place in the bottom of bowls along with tofu cubes.
6. Ladle the veggie broth across bowls, covering the noodles and tofu.
7. Top with pak choy, remaining spring onion and shredded nori, and if you like some spice, add sriracha sauce or shichimi togarshi seasoning.

#veganrecipe #plantbasedrecipe #plantbased #vegetarianrecipe #veganramen #ramenrecipe

Sharing this scares the sh*t outta me, but here goes‚Ä¶üò¨ü´£

I‚Äôve always felt like I‚Äôm ‚Äústrange‚Äù & misunderstood, & have never felt I belong in the world. I‚Äôm super sensitive, think differently, overthink, catastrophize, hyper focus & have multiple thoughts at the same time NON-STOP. Daily tasks at times are impossible for me, & sometimes just stepping out of the house feels terrifying. 

I‚Äôve just been diagnosed with ADHD & RSD (Rejection Sensitive Dysphoria) - which explains why I people-please so much & get so upset when faced with rejection, or even the perception of it - which tends to be my default reaction!

The fear of rejection is paralyzing at times, hindering me from taking action. It‚Äôs likely the reason I place immense pressure on myself to achieve perfection... a goal that is unattainable & often leads to more distress, ultimately resulting in inaction.

Throughout my life, I‚Äôve carried the belief that I am broken, incompetent, & unintelligent, harboring deep self-hatred as a result. üò¢ The burden of guilt & resentment towards myself has been overwhelming.

Living within my own mind for the past 39 years has been undeniably exhausting, at times making me wish I could escape my own thoughts. I‚Äôve long been aware that I don‚Äôt fit the mold of what is considered ‚Äúneurotypical‚Äù & I‚Äôve found relief & validation in officially getting a diagnoses. I can now help myself & show self compassion. üôåüèº

I am so thankful for my family & true friends who accept & love me no matter what. üôèüèº I‚Äôm especially grateful for Dec, who has stood by my side for the past 14 years, despite the challenges of living with me. It still surprises me that he wants to marry me haha! üòÜ

I am also grateful for the decision to start exercising in my 20s, as it is the one consistent factor that helps me tremendously.

ADHD & RSD do NOT define me, nor do they render me broken. I am wonderfully unique, just like every individual in this world. I believe there is no such thing as ‚Äúnormal‚Äù anyway. ü•∞ü´∂üèº

If you feel comfortable sharing, have you received a neurodivergent diagnosis as an adult?

We are not alone. üòò

‚ÄúYou‚Äôre meant to be a fitness professional, but you‚Äôre weak, unfit & pathetic!‚Äú - these are not words from other people, they‚Äôre words from my own head! üò´ Yep, I can be my own worst enemy! üòî Words have great power & we need to be careful what we tell ourselves. 
I‚Äôm actively working on reprogramming the way I talk to myself to be more positive, kinder & more encouraging. I need to believe in myself as I believe it‚Äôs the first & most important step towards achieving success!
This workout absolutely destroyed me. ü•µ But I did it & I‚Äôm proud of myself! üëèüèº
Getting back into my training has been a struggle. I‚Äôm lacking motivation & consistency feels like a distant dream. I‚Äôve been beating myself up over the strength & fitness I‚Äôve lost. Rehabbing injuries for several months has left me feeling discouraged, & it‚Äôs hard not to compare myself to who I used to be.

Fitness professionals like me are not immune to struggles. We may know WHAT to do, but we still have to put in the work for results. The mental game is the toughest part, especially when starting over feels like a never-ending cycle. Life throws curveballs that make it hard to stick with something long-term. But I‚Äôm determined to reclaim my fitness, strength, & get back to feeling incredible again.

Negative self-talk doesn‚Äôt do us any good. Deep down, we know this, but we need reminders. We have to consciously choose to focus on the positive, even when it feels like an uphill battle. It‚Äôs not easy, but it‚Äôs necessary.

Remember; If it were easy, everyone would be doing it. The path to fitness is tough, but it‚Äôs worth every bit of effort. So I‚Äôm taking charge, setting realistic goals, & celebrating every small victory along the way. Consistency is my anchor, & I‚Äôm committed to showing up for myself every single day.

It does get easier, I know this because I‚Äôve done it many times before. Each day I put in the effort, I know I‚Äôll get stronger & fitter. Progress may be slow, but it‚Äôs progress nonetheless. 
Let‚Äôs embrace the struggle, be proud of our efforts, & keep pushing forward. We have the power to transform our lives, & it‚Äôs time to unleash that power. üëäüèº

The last five days have been a whirlwind. I had my last day at Circle Round and left a little bit unceremoniously since we had to fly to Arizona the next morning very early. Adam‚Äòs mom had a stroke and he flew here a few days before. My mom and stepdad were in Arizona already for the gem show, and so we got to spend one glorious afternoon and evening with them before they flew back to Connecticut. 
This trip has been quite a bit different than many in the past. We‚Äôve spent a lot of time going to visit Adam‚Äòs mom in the hospital and a lot of time at home cooking and running around after Palomino. There‚Äôs a level of breathtaking that I am finding myself becoming more aware of. 
My personal breath. I realize how much I hold without breathing. And then when I finally sit down, my nervous system feels so frazzled. Adam is doing so amazing, holding space supporting his dad being so calm and loving and kind. It‚Äôs his nature. But it still fills me with gratitude to experience the calmness of his loving heart.  How he shows up in crisis and in calm. 
We have a few more days down here and then we fly home to start the next adventure which includes taking a well deserved break, pivoting @modernmacrame /closing down, dreaming up the next direction of focus for my creative entrepreneurial spirit, and BEING. Being for myself. For Pal. For Adam. For my family. For my community.
I will share more about my departure from Circle Round soon, but for now I‚Äôm focusing on being present, playing with Pal, we took our first bike ride together today!
It‚Äôs a mix of grief and gratitude.
Sending love and peace to all. 
Update, no we are not pregnant. ‚ù§Ô∏è one and done thank you. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Like over 200,000 people in the Portland area these past days, my dad‚Äôs house lost power and being over 70 and not very mobile,  with temps in the teens, he wanted us to come get him. Unfortunately all the roads to his house were closed and he was going to have to stay home for the night.
I awoke in the multiple times filled with worry for him, and for all the people without power or shelter. A fear gripping my heart for him and them. 

His phone has little power left and no way to charge it.

The next day, a generous neighbor was able to pick him up and deliver him to our heat cranked home. And I‚Äôm just so filled with gratitude for what we have. The joy of watching my dad laughing hysterically from the pleasure of getting stoned and eating his first @sarahminnick_ üçï, salad, and ice cream.
The joy of bundling up the child and playing till her lips were blue but knowing we had somewhere warm to rest.

I‚Äôm grateful for our friend Larry for helping my dad get to us.
For family of blood and chosen.

Hoping everyone out there is safe and warm tonight. Sending love and peace to all.

Happy new year dears. 
we drove to Astoria to spend the evening and day with some dear friends m, walked around the wharf and river, we watched our little children exploring. A lot of slowing down. I am hopeful that this year can bring more being present and less rushing. More deep breaths and less hustle. More connection and less fighting.
i‚Äôm also looking forward to a time when I spend a night away from my little person. and start coming back into myself, finding out who she is and stretching the possibilities of what this life has to offer..
Sending you all love and peace.

A theme lately has been
Rupture & Repair.
I'm learning about this with
my therapist as we heal
some of my childhood
traumas.
How can our nervous
systems know that it's safe
to trust someone if any
time there is a rupture,
there is no repair? That
conflict can be an
opportunity for discussion,
for showing love instead of
fear and hate?

Everyone is dealing with
their feelings about this
war/genocide in different
ways. Like @aleladiane
mentioned in her post I shared. Some mourn
privately, some post and call
to action. Some do those
things without sharing
publicly.
Some people are privately
experiencing depression, or
crisis, or myriad things.
So please show up to love
our sisters here. It's hard
enough being human, but
without compassion, how
can we learn?

And if my actions or perceived lack of
actions have hurt you in
some way,
I'm deeply sorry.
Its overwhelming to be the
owner of two businesses
(one which is closing)
Taking care of a toddler,
Being extremely under
financially resourced,
Experiencing the darkest &
scariest postpartum
depression I imagined, all
the while the world around
us in climate crisis, people
are experiencing
unbelievable suffering.
It's too much.

I've been going non stop.
Now, I'm actually sick in
bed with COVID, and have
a moment to catch my
breath. (Though I have
shortness of breath)
Thank you to everyone who
is out there being the voice
of resistance.
I'm doing my best. And if
you don't think that's
enough, then I'm sorry.
But if you have a problem,
please, how do we heal
without connection?
There is no healing through
violence.
There is no healing through
giving someone the cold
shoulder.
There is no healing through
avoidance.
We heal through our
suffering being welcomed
in, shared, and not by being
pushed out.

Sending love to all

All who are suffering 
All who experience pain in their own ways. 

And to 
All who are celebrating 
(Because we need to also hold dear the beauty right in front of us) our health, the faces of those we love, our friends and community, our children.

From @biddytarot :
The king of wands

The King of Wands represents pure fire energy in its masculine form. Unlike the other Wands court cards, the King is not so interested in creation and creativity, or in dreaming up ideas and implementing them himself. Instead, he is more inclined to take an idea and then enlist others to help him actualise it. Thus, when the King of Wands appears in a Tarot reading, it is a sign you are stepping into the role of a visionary leader, ready to direct your people towards a common goal. You have a clear vision of where you want to go, and now you are manifesting that vision with the support of those around you. Others naturally gravitate towards you because you are charismatic, focused, and determined, and they believe in you and your vision. They want to be a part of what you are manifesting and are here to support you one hundred percent of the way. You are also masterful at getting other people to do your work for you while keeping them on-side throughout the process.
The King of Wands reminds you to lead your life with intent, vision and a long-term view. You have a grand idea of what is truly possible, and you will stop at nothing to see it through. You achieve a lot because you are clear about your future direction and how you will get there ‚Äì and do not waste your time on activities or relationships you believe will lead nowhere. You never just go with the flow; instead, you prefer to embark on a direct and robust course of action. And you are inspired by long-term, sustainable success, wanting to have a lasting impact. You are here to leave a legacy.
The appearance of the King of Wands also suggests that an opportunity is presenting itself to you, and you now have the power to take on the challenge. You are the determining factor in this situation. If you want it to be successful, it will. And equally, if you do not fully commit to it, this seed will struggle to blossom and grow. You can create any outcome you wish, so be mindful about your intentions and vision. You hold the power.

How often do you stop to measure your successes? I find it is usually easier to remember the difficult times, but in this moment, I would like to honor all that we have accomplished.

In the past 10 years since starting Modern Macram√©, I have traveled the world teaching plant and wall-hanging workshops. I always dreamed of traveling for work, and I was lucky to be welcomed to teach in Mexico City, Barcelona, Copenhagen, Kyoto, Berlin, London, Amsterdam, and many more places. I visited our rope supplier in Turkey. 

In 2018 wrote a book about macram√© that finally paid out the advance this week! Woot! (a new book idea is brewing!)
 

I toured the USA in a mini van with my friend Caitlin teaching over 50 workshops from coast to coast over 3 months to celebrate that book.

I worked with amazing women in the studio and across the world, my teammates and my students who taught me so much about how to lead, how to be kind, how to ask for what you need, and how to be human. I am still learning. You know who you are.

We as a company sold over $3 million worth of rope, classes, and other craft supplies.
 
Our work helped launch the careers of small craft business owners around the globe. - continued in slides and comments

Goodbye my sweet friend. I‚Äôll miss you forever. 10 years wasn‚Äôt long enough. 
There are 100‚Äôs of photos and videos of Donut Underfoot PorterKatz from the past 10 years, it‚Äôs impossible to pick 10. There will be more to share for sure.

The story of Donut:
After about a year of living together one day Adam said what do you think about getting a dog. I thought hey how about we foster one instead. We have such busy lifestyles and maybe we should see if bringing a dog into our lives will be a good fit. That was on a Friday. On Monday this little scruffy sickly fearful creature showed up to our house,  he had eaten an entire plastic bowl and wouldn‚Äôt eat in front of us for months. After just a few days we decided there was no way we could give him back and we just we named him Donut after the tiny donut shaped ball he curled up into. Circa 2013?

Donut was our eternal adventure buddy. He came everywhere with us. He came to work every single day to the Macram√© studio and Adam‚Äôs screen printing space. He climbed ladders. He rode in backpacks. He hiked mountains. He‚Äôs snuggled under blankets and sleeping bags in tents and in the back of our Ford truck. He was a protector. All that he wanted was love. And we gave him as much as we could.

Feels like ‚òÄÔ∏è training with this guy lately!

Just about a year ago, I happened to watch some new people train their dogs. I remember I was so impressed. Their sessions started with intention - there was a warm up routine (something completely foreign to me at that point). Then the entire session just flowed effortlessly between obedience and play. There was no awkward down time or disengagement between the handler and the dog. The dogs looked so happy to be working and the handlers were clear and focused in their communication. I remember thinking, wow, how do we get on that level ü§©

Fast forward to 2024 and it feels like we are finally making some moves! There‚Äôs still a ton of work to do, but I‚Äôve been so grateful to learn from some super talented teams these past few months. Thanks for always inspiring me @shaunancyr @workingsdragon @spicycanine and everyone at @groundzeroschutzhund üî•

ü¶∑ Brushing their teeth daily
ü¶∑ Regularly hitting annual veterinary dental visits to get x-rays and deep cleanings (just like us humans have)
ü¶∑ Avoiding super hard chews like bones and nylon chew toys
ü¶∑ Giving a daily vet-developed @stellaandchewys dental chews

Hello from the girlies! They have been loving the extra space at our new place, but now that we live in a 2-story house, I‚Äôve incorporated some changes to minimize risk of joint issues and osteoarthritis, especially since these two are getting up there in age (nearly 10 and 11 ü•∫)

‚òëÔ∏è Block off stairs to prevent excessive stress on the joints
‚òëÔ∏è Add joint supporting supplements to their daily meals
‚òëÔ∏è Cover highly trafficked areas in the home with rugs to reduce slipping
‚òëÔ∏è Reduce calories to account for slower metabolisms

We got these tips from @vca - make sure to check them out for more pet health info!

What a year for Kibo! 

We kicked off 2023 by showing in Best In Show and securing his spot as the #4 White Shepherd in the USA. My goal this year was to switch focus from conformation to sports, and we ended up picking up some NACSW nosework titles and passing his IGP BH-VT! The year was not only filled with early mornings, long drives, and training sessions, but also so many good times spent with friends both new and old, laughing, playing, hiking, eating, gaming, shopping, swimming‚Ä¶ all with Kibo by my side. 

In just a few days he will be 3 years old and we‚Äôll embark on yet another year of fun together. Onwards and upwards to 2024!

Santorini, the most magical of the Greek islands. This island of the Cyclades offers a multitude of activities to its visitors.

From discovering its historical heritage to watching the sunset over the Aegean Sea, to black sand beaches and boat trips, there is something for everyone. Here's a rundown of the best things to do in Santorini.

Fira, the capital, is one of the places not to be missed. With its white and blue houses, small cobbled streets, fashion boutiques and luxury hotels with swimming pools, it represents the essence of the island.

The village of Oia is also not to be missed for its spectacular beauty

The archaeological site of Akrotiri is an exciting getaway for history and culture lovers.

The ancient city of Thera is also worth a visit to learn more about the island's history

For food lovers, the Greek cuisine in Santorini is not to be missed, especially the famous souvlaki

Boat trips around the island are a pleasant way to discover the wonders of Santorini. The boat cruise, which allows you to visit the volcanic island and to reach the top of the crater of the volcano Nea Kameni, is a very popular activity

Sea kayaking from the red beach is also a fun activity that allows you to discover the volcanic coast and the fabulous sea caves

To finish the day, the sunset on Oia is one of the most famous activities in Santorini.

However, for those who are looking to watch the sunset from the water, the alignments may be better in Fira or Imerovigli.

Take a voyage back in time to Rothenburg, a medieval German town that is considered the most charming in Bavaria.

Rothenburg has a rich history that dates back to the Middle Ages. The town was founded in 1170 and thrived due to its strategic location on an important trade route. The town's historic buildings have been preserved in their original state and offer visitors a unique glimpse into life in the Middle Ages.

Start by walking through the streets of the old town, admiring the historic buildings and beautiful views.

Be sure to visit the city hall, built in 1250, as well as climb the steps of the clock tower for a spectacular view of the city's rooftops, churches and historic buildings.

Last but not least, don't miss a visit to the medieval fortress called Burggarten, which also offers a breathtaking view of the city. It's the perfect place to take memorable pictures.

Which photo do you prefer?

Don't forget to share with a friend who loves the Middle Ages

We have made some changes since these were rendered over a year ago, but the general feel of the space remains the same. Warm, cozy, welcoming, and with big bright windows!

It‚Äôs been SO insane seeing this space take shape, bit by bit, right in front of me after imagining it for so many years. We started the design process for the house back in 2020, and in some ways it feels like it‚Äôs gone by in a flash, and in other ways it feels like it‚Äôs taken forever lol üòÇ

But I‚Äôm incredibly grateful that all the hard work has resulted in a real solid structure taking shape before our eyes!

I can‚Äôt wait to share more about budgeting for design choices in a blog post soon (working on it at the moment, hoping to have it up next week! ü§û) In the meantime, have a wonderful leap day my friend!!!

PS‚ÄîDon‚Äôt let fear keep you from taking a wild, ridiculous leap. With some work + a dash of stubbornness, you never know where it might take you! üòä

Spring + blueberry season is just around the corner, and there‚Äôs no better way to enjoy it than with a @empress1908gin Blueberry Negroni! ü´ê #sponsor

It has THE perfect balance of herbs and fruit, with a wonderfully pleasant bitter hint that‚Äôs signature of the classic negroni, this is one to bookmark! üôå

Enjoy my friends + #SipResponsibly! ü•É

ü´ê Blueberry Negroni ü´ê
Makes 2 Servings

2 ounces @empress1908gin
2 ounces Luxardo bitter bianco
1 1/2 ounces sweet vermouth
1 ounce blueberry concentrate

Stir together all ingredients in a mixing glass with a few cubes of ice. Strain and pour into 2 chilled rocks glasses filled with ice. Serve immediately.

Blueberry Concentrate

1 cup blueberries, fresh or frozen
1 tablespoon finely grated orange zest
2 tablespoons sugar
1/2 cup water

Bring to a boil over med-high heat. Reduce heat to low and simmer until blueberries release their juices, about 10 minutes. Place a sieve over a small bowl and strain, using a spoon to press the blueberries to get as much liquid as possible. Reserve the liquid and discard the blueberry pulp. Cool to room temperature then refrigerate in an airtight container.

Where we ended up, and how we got there ‚û°Ô∏èüëÄ I‚Äôm breaking down how I use layering to add dimension +  texture in captures, and you can get the full behind-the-scenes emailed to you by commenting LAYER below or via the link in my profile! üíå

And if you‚Äôre wondering what this golden concotion is, it‚Äôs a creamy and ultra-comforting roasted parsnip soup üçúüíõ

Because I‚Äôm obsessed with all things both salty and sweet, I caramelized some leeks and pureed them into the soup with the roasted parsnips, and sprinkled some on top as well for texture.

Leeks have much less moisture than onions, so they caramelize much quicker in the pan. But be careful! That also means it‚Äôs easier to burn them if you‚Äôre not paying attention since they dry out faster. üî•

And for a slight bit of crunch and a wonderfully toasted flavor, there‚Äôs some roasted hazelnuts sprinkled on top. The tired cook might say ‚Äúmeh, I don‚Äôt really need those‚Äù and cut them from the grocery list, but let me insist, that you *do* in fact need them. They are SUCH a good complement to the roasted parsnip soup, and if you get tired of the same texture easily like I do, they add a really nice crunch to an otherwise super smooth soup. And they‚Äôre super easy to make (less than 10 minutes to toast them, I promise!) Live a little and go for it, I say! üôå

You can find the recipe at AdventuresInCooking.com üòãWishing you the most fantastic week ahead, my friends! üíõüíõüíõ

Brightening up winter with a vibrant + refreshing @empress1908gin Grapefruit Gimlet, made with Empress Elderflower Rose Gin, fresh grapefruit juice, grapefruit simple syrup, and a splash of bubbles! üçä

üçä Grapefruit Simple Syrup

¬Ω cup sugar
¬Ω cup water
3 tablespoons fresh squeezed grapefruit juice

In a small pot, simmer together sugar and water for 10 minutes, add grapefruit juice & stir to combine. Take off heat, allow to cool, then refrigerate.

üçä Grapefruit Gimlet Fizz (serves 2)

4 ounces @empress1908gin (1/2 cup)
2 ounces grapefruit juice (¬º cup)
2 ounce grapefruit simple syrup (¬º cup)
2 ounces sparkling mineral water
Rosemary sprig for garnish

Combine #EmpressGin, grapefruit juice, and syrup together in a large mixing glass and stir to combine. Evenly distribute between two coupe glasses, top with sparkling water, garnish with rosemary sprig, and enjoy!

In essence, early farming was a game of chance.

Whiskey, a popular distilled alcohol, originates from a fermented grain mash. 

With barley, corn, rye, and wheat as the primary ingredients, it shares a close kinship with beer - distill a beer and voila, you have a basic form of whiskey!

Consider Scotch, distilled twice and born in Scotland, or Irish whiskey, hailing from Ireland and typically distilled thrice. 

Then there‚Äôs Bourbon, a uniquely American whiskey, predominantly from Kentucky and Tennessee, mandatorily containing at least 51 percent corn and aged in charred white oak barrels.

Americans sure loved their spirits, and that love affair birthed the infamous sin taxes we know today, levied on our beloved alcohol and tobacco. 

Even the great President George Washington was skeptical of this tax, but after touring Virginia and Pennsylvania in 1791, he found local elected officials toasting to the idea of a whiskey tax. With newfound conviction, he returned to Philadelphia, championing the legislation. 

It‚Äôs interesting to note that in those times, a whopping 96 percent of the American population resided east of the Appalachian Mountains, the very folks the whiskey tax targeted. 

Meanwhile, the remaining 4 percent lived west of the Appalachians, in what was then known as the West, where corn was king and distilling whiskey was just part of the subsistence lifestyle. 

And thus, the sin tax saga began.

The Cold War era, known for its nuclear arms race, also saw a less publicized contest between the U.S. and the Soviet Union. 

A race to the depths of the Earth.

In the late 1950s, the U.S. embarked on Project Mohole, an ambitious plan to drill through the Earth‚Äôs crust from a ship off the Mexican coast. 

Despite the drilling reaching a depth of 183 meters, the project failed to hit the mantle. 

On the other side of the world, the Soviets started a similar project in 1970 on the Kola Peninsula, close to Norway. By 1989, they had achieved a staggering depth of 12,262 meters, deeper than Mount Everest is high, and deeper than the Marianas Trench. 

A testament to human ambition, it‚Äôs fascinating to realize there were battles fought not just in space, but also within our very own Earth. 

In the end, it‚Äôs not about who won or lost, but the lengths we go to satiate our curiosity.

The U.S. Constitution doesn‚Äôt explicitly mention a jury of one‚Äôs peers. Instead, the Sixth Amendment grants the right to an impartial jury. 

Yet, the concept of a jury of peers is deeply ingrained in our legal culture. The jury‚Äôs power is virtually limitless, free to reach any conclusion for any reason. 

This leads us to the idea of jury nullification. Not a formal law, but a concept founded on the premise that juries can‚Äôt be penalized for their conclusions. 

In the past, U.S. juries have chosen not to convict in cases where they deemed laws unjust. 

This underlines the importance of the jury process in upholding freedoms within our legal system.

Shakespeare, the name synonymous with English literature, was not always held in such high regard.
