Halloween, first referred to by this name in 1775, traces its roots to the ancient Celtic pagan festival of Samhain. 

This festival, celebrated on November 1st, signaled the end of harvest and the onset of winter, and was the highlight of the Celtic calendar. 

As Christianity spread, it absorbed the customs and traditions of Samhain, morphing them into Christian celebrations that coincided with the same period. 

In England, Halloween traditions slowly faded and were replaced by Guy Fawkes Day on November 5th. However, in Scotland and Ireland, Halloween continued to be celebrated with fervor.

The early settlers in the Americas brought these traditions with them, with Anglican and Catholic settlers both observing the holiday, but not the Puritans up in New England - they were generally against everything.

In conclusion, Halloween is deeply rooted in ancient traditions that have evolved and survived the passage of time.

My 20th year Anniversary @mercedesbenz

As a young boy I dreamed to work for @mercedesamg
I was fascinated from the Brand, the passion the two founders (Aufrecht and Melcher) had and the pure strength to get their dream come true! It had a huge impact on me to see nothing can stop you in life if you really want it!

As a young kid I wanted to follow into the footsteps of my great grandfather, grandfather and especially my dad who all worked 45 years for Daimler. But I never forgot my personal goal and this was AMG. On the weekends I drove to Affalterbach only to admire the cars and feel the the atmosphere there.

After years of working for Mercedes-Benz
I grabbed the chance and started working for AMG. I want to share here on Instagram how it feels to work for the Best Performance and Sports Car Brand in the world as an engine builder.

Sometimes it‚Äôs time to reflect how things can turn out in your life if you are ready to do it and work hard for it!
To be an engine builder for Mercedes-AMG is not only a job for me. It was my dream and now I can truly say, I am able to live my dream everyday. I really put all my heart and soul into my work.

It is a big honor for me to see the love, the passion for my work and the love for Mercedes-AMG you all share here with me.

Thank you to all the Ladies and Gentlemans all over the world with an engine handcrafted from me, to all AMG, Pagani customers and fans worldwide that share the passion and love for my work here on Instagram.

You all here make this Brand as special as it is to me. We all share so many moments together and became a big family. 
Thank you to all of you for that!

Back in the days, the most powerful AMG V8 series engine of all time, the most expressive design, the most elaborate aerodynamics, the most intelligent material mix, the most distinctive driving dynamics: For the new Mercedes-AMG GT Black Series (combined fuel consumption 12.8 l/100 km, combined CO2 emissions 292 g/km)[1], the Affalterbach designers have pulled out all the stops when it comes to the art of vehicle design.

The super sports car perfectly embodies the brand‚Äôs rich tradition in motorsport, as well its many years of expertise in developing complete vehicles which impress in every respect. The result is an output of 537 kW (730 hp) from a V8 engine with a ‚Äöflat‚Äò crankshaft, combined with active aerodynamics and a design which stems directly from the current AMG GT3 racing car.

Different designs of V8 engines.

The design of a V8 engine gives designers plenty of room to play with in one key element: the crank arrangement on the crankshaft.
The result is the most powerful V8 series engine from Mercedes-AMG.

The GT Black Series engine may be based on the AMG 4.0-litre V8 biturbo engine with dry sump lubrication, but it has been given the new internal code M178 LS2 due to the numerous modifications. It achieves 730hp at 6700-6900 rpm and delivers a maximum torque of 800Nm at 2000-6000 rpm. New camshafts and exhaust manifolds are adapted to the new firing order and further improve the gas cycle.

Both twin scroll exhaust turbochargers are mounted in anti-friction bearings, as in the top-of-the-range four-door AMG GT CoupeÃÅ, which optimises their throttle response even further. However, in the Black Series, the turbochargers have been given a larger compressor wheel, meaning that both can deliver a total of 1100 kg air per hour.

‚ÄúAs I made these images, I was becoming aware that my body was remembering what it had gone through and was going through,‚Äù the photographer Veronica Cruz (@veronicacrruz) says. ‚ÄúBut I was also learning that it was okay to let it out and feel all of this without shame and without feeling like I had to hide it.‚Äù
.
In Little Earthquakes, the artist navigates childhood trauma through photography. Cruz was raped as a child. At the age of twelve, she had emergency brain surgery and was hospitalized due to an AVM, an abnormal connection between the arteries and veins in her brain.
.
Little Earthquakes is a work-in-progress, following the artist as she revisits the past and copes with the ongoing tremors reverberating in the aftermath of trauma. In some ways, the photographs represent an acknowledgment of the artist‚Äôs younger self‚Äîseen figuratively in an empty swing set.
.
Each time the artist herself appears throughout Little Earthquakes, whether she‚Äôs gazing directly at the camera or cradling her body, she reinforces the simple fact of her survival: she‚Äôs still here.

This has always been one of my favorite stretches, so I snuck in a few extra rounds after teaching today ‚ù§Ô∏è 

I haven‚Äôt had much time or energy to train recently, but it feels good to sneak it small moments here and there when I can. Usually I try to prioritize my training, but right now I‚Äôm focused on making one of my biggest dreams come true: creating a home that I never want to leave and that I can bring my students and friends to ü•π

Somewhere along the way we got this idea that change is something to be feared. But what if, instead of fearing change, we actually gave ourselves the space to grow into something different, something unexpected. The unknown might be scary, but it‚Äôs also the only place that endless possibilities exist. No one knows what the future holds for any of us, so instead of spending another second focusing on the things I can no longer do, I‚Äôm going to spend each day finding out what I CAN do and being extremely grateful for those things. Because one day that will change, too. 

Thank you all so much for the love and support on my last post, I didn‚Äôt realize how much better I would feel after sharing with you all ü•≤

I was inspired by @erin.skye.circus and @_fleximon to try this leg movement that they did in handstand, anyone else want to try it out?

I‚Äôm glad I knew exactly how much of a gift it was every time I was able to press into handstand, because it is a skill I will likely never be able to do again. 

It‚Äôs pretty amazing that I was able to do any of the harder handstand skills I did with a decaying bone in my wrist, and I‚Äôm so grateful I was able to push it as hard as I did when I did.

I got an MRI recently that confirmed my fears, and the bone in my wrist that is decaying has started to fragment and other parts of my wrist are becoming affected now as well. I didn‚Äôt need imaging to tell me things were getting worse, I could feel it. The good news is I can still do a few handstands here and there for now and demo basic skills in classes, but I will no longer be training handstands regularly or pushing to advance my skills at all. 

There‚Äôs too much to say about all of this, so I‚Äôm not going to say much else right now. I‚Äôm so lucky because I have a lot of amazing things happening in my life that I can focus on, and I can continue sharing my love for handstands through teaching and my students. 

At this point all treatment options are experimental, but don‚Äôt worry I will definitely be over here getting whatever experiments done that I can üî¨

My mom had some major breakthroughs last week, including her first unassisted hang since she was a kid! ü§©ü•πüéâ 

She did a multiple reps like this hovering her feet for a few seconds each time. Working with the smith machine has made it more approachable for her, but I‚Äôll get her hanging on a taller bar soon. 

More importantly, after a week of strength training (specifically working on hanging and rows) my mom was able to reach behind her back with no shoulder pain, which is huge for her! 

I‚Äôm in Michigan for the next 10 days but I‚Äôll do a few more sessions with my mom when I‚Äôm back in Maryland for Christmas!

My mom wants to learn how to lift weights, so here‚Äôs a recap of what we did on her first session! 

She has been teaching yoga for a long time and is very active, but her doctor recommended that she build more leg muscle.  She‚Äôs never really lifted weights (more than a few pound dumbbells), so we are building from the ground up with both compound and isolated exercises. 

We started with a standing warm up focusing on balance and leg mobility (I couldn‚Äôt film everything!)
Then we worked on hanging with supported hangs and scapular shrugs (grip strength is super important for older adults and also hanging is great for shoulder health + more)

Then she did:
3 x 10 Goblet Squats
2 x 10 RDLs
2 x 10 Leg Extension Machine (single leg)
2 x 10 Hamstring Curl (both legs)
2 x 15 Hip Abduction
2 x 10 Hip Adduction

Let me know if you found this interesting and I will film her again next time ‚ù§Ô∏è

My account was hacked on May 27. This is why you have been seeing uncharacteristic behavior, including username change, contact information change, and posting of other dogs on this account. I regained access last week, only to be rehacked five minutes later. The hacker was intent on impersonating me, and was planning on telling you that Milo has died and that the account will change direction. THIS IS NOT TRUE. Milo is alive and very well. I was merely taking a break from social media, unaware that this would expose me as a target of hacking. The hacker has re-registered my old username to squat the account. At this point, I'm unsure whether he will find his way back into this account. Ignacio, if you're reading this, PLEASE leave us alone. We just want to share Milo with the world in peace. To our loyal followers, thanks for sticking with us through this mess üòö Please report if you start seeing suspicious behavior again!

This week the USDA announced that there are fewer farms in the U.S. than at any time since 1850, and 40% of them are owned by people over age 65.  In most industrialized countries, farmers are less than 2% of the population and shrinking.  Here, Doug Hellinger is driving a weed sprayer past the homestead that his grandmother established near Shelby, Montana, shortly after 1909, when the Homestead Act gave 320 acres for free if you farmed the land for five years.  At that time, there were 72 families per 36 sq miles, and today, just 8 people remain, including Doug.

Looking for covers for my next book today, and I came across this forgotten image from the soybean harvest in Brazil two years ago.  Soybean production in Brazil is almost ten times what it was in 1985, and those numbers continue to rise to meet China‚Äôs growing demand for pig food. Much of that new production is from land that was once forest.

Volcanic crater of Wau al Namus (hole of mosquitos) in Arabic. 
This massive volcano can easily be seen in satellite views of Southern Libya, as a large black smear in the wind-scoured sands of the Sahara.  The inner crater is bordered by a chain of small salt lakes which are sumps for underground springs). Outside the rim are small black dunes of windblown volcanic ejecta.  It was difficult getting there with my motorized paraglider during the time of Gadaffi, but would be even more complicated today. Carpe diem!
So nice to see my photo above the fold on front page of today‚Äôs @NYTimes!  To see more and read the story on-line, go to link in bio.

Herding over 600 sheep down from the remote high pasture of the Aletsch Glacier Valley in Switzerland.  So happy to see this story about the effects of climate change in the Alps in today‚Äôs @nytimes

Herding 145,000 sheep and goats onto a livestock carrier in the port of Berbera, Somaliland last July for shipment to Mecca in Saudi Arabia, where 2.6 million animals were ritually sacrificed on the third day of the Hajj pilgrimage.  According to today‚Äôs @NYTimes, Somaliland has just granted military use of this sleepy deepwater port to landlocked Ethiopia, allowing access to the busy shipping lanes of the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden.  No monetary terms were disclosed, but the deal makes Ethiopia the first nation to recognize the sovereignty of Somaliland, a self-declared democratic republic in one of the world‚Äôs poorest regions.  Last year, live animal exports were 85% of Somaliland‚Äôs export earnings and 30% of its GDP, but that may be about to change.

Viktoriia M. (not her real name), a member of the National Guard at the Chornobyl Nuclear Power Plant, is overcome with emotion as she recounts the harrowing story of her husband. Also a member of the Ukrainian National Guard, he was detained by Russian troops during their occupation of Chornobyl two years ago.

She is heartbroken because she has not yet received any sign that he is alive. Without knowing his whereabouts or the conditions he may be enduring, he is still one of the "10,000 [prisoners of war] believed to remain in Russian custody." - Forbes, 10/21/23. I am personally devastated by the diminishing support for Ukraine by the US and other western countries.

In November of last year, I photographed Viktoriia in an unmarked room to protect her and her husband's identities. She remains cautious and fearful for his fate.

I have been documenting the aftermath of the Chornobyl catastrophe for many decades. Since the Russian occupation after the start of the war in Ukraine, I have felt that my work remains unfinished. Following 10 months of negotiations, I was finally granted permission to re-enter the exclusion zone last October. Pay attention to this page over the coming weeks as I will be posting more images and stories from this trip.

World-renowned artist Joseph Beuys, easily identified by his iconic felt hat, kisses his wife Eva outside their home and studio at the Drakeplatz in D√ºsseldorf in 1978.

This photograph will be included in my upcoming bilingual book BEUYS LAND, published by Edition Lammerhuber, which will be printed later this month and available April/May 2024.

@thephotosociety #ValentinesDay #BEUYSLAND #JosephBeuys #artist

Joseph Beuys, one of the most influential artists of the 20th century, talking about his art in the kitchen of his residence/studio at Drakeplatz in D√ºsseldorf. This photograph will be included in my upcoming book BEUYS LAND, published by Edition Lammerhuber, available late April of 2024. 

BEUYS LAND is the first book to centralize the natural landscape of the Lower Rhine and Joseph Beuys' purported birthplace, Kleve, within the artist's universe. In January 1978, I captured how Beuys revisited his past in Kleve and its Lower Rhine environs, the place where his journey began. My collection of photographs predominantly features Beuys amidst the characteristic landscape of dykes, ponds, poplar-lined avenues, and the local populace. These images palpably convey the interdependence of Beuys' art concept and the starkness of his landscape. The book also includes never-before-published photographs of Beuys and his wife Eva at their residence/studio in D√ºsseldorf and the Basler Fasnacht (Carnival of Basel) in Switzerland.

Accompanying my photographs, cultural scientist Frank Mehring explores how Beuys derived inspiration and energy from the Lower Rhine's roots, honed his ecological consciousness, and nurtured the artistic dynamism that propelled him to the forefront of the global art scene.

Today, January 23, 2024 marks the 38th anniversary of Joseph Beuys‚Äô passing.

This photograph was taken inside the highly contaminated reactor #4 of the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant (Ukraine, 2011). After the explosion, cleanup crews initially had to pass over hazardous ladders to a section underneath the melted core with life-threatening contamination. To facilitate faster access, a daunting hallway called the leaning staircase was erected. When I entered this area of the reactor, radiation was still so high that access was limited to less than 30 minutes per day. 

#Chernobyl #thenextchapter #chornobyl #Ukraine #Kickstarter @kickstarter

Silent nursery inside the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone. On the day the Nuclear Power Plant‚Äôs reactor #4 blew up, children oblivious to the nuclear accident played in this kindergarten of the reactor‚Äôs company town, Pripyat. The following day they were evacuated and had to leave everything behind ‚Äì even their treasured dolls and toys.

I have been given the rare opportunity to return to the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone and reactor #4 itself to document the highly contaminated areas beneath the New Safe Confinement and meet with victims, liquidators, and the few remaining returnees who are still living in the Zone. 

As traditional media outlets lack the necessary funds to support long-term reporting, I have once again turned to the Kickstarter community, colleagues, friends, and followers for assistance in this endeavor.

Flew to the land down under few days ago and I finally got to see Canberra. I must say this beautiful city is more quiet and laidback as compared to the vibrant and busy Sydney.

With many things in mind, visiting the National Gallery of Australia is on the top our list. Inside it we saw a lot of amazing masterpieces, but what struck me the most is James Turrell's 'Within without' Skyspace, a viewing chamber (or a "stupa") highlighted by turquoise water that surrounds it. This work shows the way we percieve the sky depending on the time of the day. They say it is at its most dramatic and complex form during dawn and dusk, marking the transition between day and night. Truly a remarkable work of art where nature, art, and architecture meet!

Excited to share more snaps and stories from the many things we saw and learned about this city. Big thanks to my travel partner @bigskynationph for keeping us connected everywhere we go with their travel wi-fi!

The past weeks have been a roller coaster ride of ideas, emotions and realizations for me. I came across things that I never really expected. These have been going around my head for a long time now and found myself lost in the middle of nowhere, but it‚Äôs okay.

I guess, there‚Äôs this certain level of wonder that you get when you‚Äôre lost and that it isn‚Äôt bad at all. That‚Äôs how life goes anyway. Clear your mind, cherish the things you see in every stop, and keep going till you find yourself on track again. There are far better things ahead than any we leave behind.

As cliche as it sounds, never stop exploring. üîú

The beetle of rebirth ü™≤üåû
At the end of November 2021 we were at a friends house about to leave when a golden beetle posed on my hand. It had been a long time since I saw one or at least payed close attention to it. I feel that many times we experience things often but don‚Äôt really give importance to them until we feel it is needed, then it becomes something meaningful. I started drawing the beetle on my notebook, carefully placed the insect on my finger it was holding my index with his tiny legs and thought about a ring! 
It gave me nostalgia of when the world was different and when we could travel, reminded me of our time in Egypt and in some way gave me hope, Cairo 2019 was also where I first saw a beetle ring from Tutankamon in the museum. I was amazed by Egyptian culture, art and mostly jewelry I thought it was cool but I never really questioned the symbolism of the elements and characters they used back then and why, but that day the golden beetle that posed on my hand made me curious and I started reaserching what it means, the meaning varies depending the culture but what I took from the Egyptians is that: the beetle symbolized the sun, a new day, a new opportunity, a cicle, knowing that the sun rises every day no matter what, rebirth! I thought the meaning was beautiful and felt like the right timing for me to start a process of ‚Äúrebirth‚Äù this was right before 2021 ended, 

which had been a though year, I was not feeling too motivated, my grandma had just passed away a couple months before, and some little struggles that made me feel a bit stuck and not at my best. I didn‚Äôt know it at the time but from that day it was going to take 5 months to have the finished ring in my hands. Not because the actual process takes that long but in a way I wanted to have it ready whenever I felt better with myself, finishing this ring will mean to have a rebirth in a way, learnt the lessons, feel more motivated and in a better mental space.

On this day in 2020 I was waking up to snow shoe in Andermatt, Switzerland. Just one of the many adventures as one of two representatives from the United States for their 2-week Global Influencer Summit. I would return home to go speak for my first time at WPPI  just weeks before the world would shut down.

My efforts shifted to caring more for my family, and taking a job that I truly and happily thought would be the rest of my life, but it did not turn out that way. And for the last 4 years I was happy to set down what I knew to focus on what was in front of me even if the breath in my creative lungs was very shallow.

Over the last 4 months I‚Äôve been sorting out next steps. I was recently challenged to put together a reel of my work to share. For all the ways my short memory and impuslivity have served me in moments of needed courage, it hasn‚Äôt always helped me stay organized... so, it took some time. Going back through the work over the last 16 years reminded me how fortunate I have been to do something I loved for so long that has allowed me to see so much of this beautiful planet. For years, whether it was a brand or a fellow creative, I was able to be in very personal conversations with people that wanted to communicate something uniquely their own to the world. The drive to create beautiful things is a bass note in the soul of so many people, and being in that space was much more rewarding than it was work. I‚Äôm hoping photography, creative direction, and making beautiful things is not just a part of my past, but even if it were, it‚Äôs been very formational in who I am now.

I hope you‚Äôll watch, and if it at all makes sense to share it with someone who might want to see it please do. You can find the full resolution version on my bio link

I saw @karlieplace post a bit of this editing style on a reel yesterday and I just thought it was amazing. Shout out to hers, you should definitely go check it out. 

When I see the dodge/burn notes on old film prints it‚Äôs a reminder that the art and intention of the shot doesn‚Äôt end until it‚Äôs delivered. I imagine some people would rather enjoy the magic without seeing how the sausage is made but I LOVE editing and always have.

I came up in this industry at a time where there was this odd mystique and elitism that I thankfully avoided, but I saw it discourage SO many people. And there was a tension because my income was also tied to education regarding editing and presets, and carving out a brand that was uniquely my voice. I‚Äôd much rather contribute to the shared pool of liberating knowledge so that the beautiful thing you were meant to do is not trapped behind something as dull as tone curves and split toning. 

The anchors of journalistic integrity are different than those for eliciting emotion. But you are also free to, and encouraged to, be unashamed about what does and doesn‚Äôt land with your creative preference. Just don‚Äôt make that the primary thing about your engagements with people on the internet. 

As always if you have questions about my process, whether it be gear, software, how I think about what I do, or anything else I‚Äôd so much rather communicate than get a ‚Äòlike‚Äô.

Little Life update:
The sun has been shining nearly all Month. I lay like a cat curled in the warm embrace. I notice how different everything is when the sun is out. How sparkly the rivers are. Three black cockatoos soar every afternoon over the forest canopy. 
I Planted a tiny peach tree in the garden 3 years ago and harvested 30 or so juicy sweet peaches üçë this week. 
My best friend rang me to tell me she is falling in love. I love the first moments of love. I live for it. The tales, the excitement, the total ecstasy. I can feel it, experience it just by hearing her through the phone. I have been jogging each day, swimming in the river every second. I‚Äôm trying to figure out a way to also include yoga and meditation into my daily practice again. Sometimes I find it hard to blend family life and one‚Äôs self. It‚Äôs as if I‚Äôm so immersed in one, I completely neglected the other and vice versa. 
Does the mother exist within one‚Äôs self,?
Or is one‚Äôs self seperate to the mother ?
This is something I ask frequently at the moment.
We had to let our rooster go because he kept attacking Zu, but than our friends gave us a new rooster and he is so cuddly and nice.
I find life works better when I just let go. 
My love for flowers keeps deepening and my
plant allies all over this beautiful planet just keep paving the way. Spring smells so good everywhere. 
Multitasking is such a disservice to me, but I keep doing it, how do I stop ? 
My Dad always said ‚Äòyou make your own fun‚Äô and it really is true. 
I‚Äôm learning to re write the word bored and replace it with peace. 
Nothing feels better than a really deep drawn out orgasm. 
I really truely do miss Italy.

How much happier would we be if we spent more time moving with the force of life? Dancing, singing, making love, feeling sexy, walking barefoot in the woods, floating down rivers, swimming in the ocean, growing flowers, eating from the garden, spotting animals, sharing stories and gazing at the moon - rather than always pushing ourselves along a path that we think is leading us to where we want to go?¬†Status, achievements, looking a certain way, Career, money, the next new ‚Äòthing‚Äô.. these are really quite unimportant when it comes to quality of life, but our minds are brainwashed. I suggest sitting, closing down your eyes and picture pulling your heart out of your chest and give it a big wash with sacred water. I pray daily: great spirit, help me live more in my heart. Let my heart open to the warmth magic which is life. The richness of truly living, the present moment is invaluable. 

We owe it to ourselves to acknowledge that our mind is so much smaller than feminine life force within us. As is the way most modern societies are living. Right now, a lot of us are closed in by fear. Fear for health (eat well, exercise, love yourself and cleanse your thoughts) fear of authority, fear of dying, fear of being seen, fear fear fear. We are living so SMALL! You know it if all of a sudden you do something that is stepping out of that fear-
We can taste the beginning of richness in something as simple as a naked cold water, river swim. This is the real path to living .  The divine feminine way which we all must find a way back to. For our planet. For our own survival. 
What if we were to let go of the expectations we had for ourselves, and just became more free to be. To have this human experience. To feel content with just living and loving?

From my Happy place

There is this incredible art to giving and receiving and it really is one of the secrets to this life journey. I‚Äôve noticed that the more I put one hand out to give, the other, as if by universal law begins to receive. I think the only purpose to this life is to love. To feel. To make others feel. It‚Äôs a very important job your doing if your following your bliss. Don‚Äôt let anything else steer you in a (lower) direction. 
We are all made up by layers of past, present and future. Maturity and childlike wonder go hand in hand. We are all living breathing star constellations so we might as well become the star. Of our show.

BENEATH THE OPERA HOUSE, PALAIS Garnier in Paris there is a lake. Crime reporter and Opera critic Gaston Leroux used it as the background for Phantom of the Opera. The "lake" is actually a tank of groundwater and the Paris fire brigade use it for dive training. I photographed the training and got the rare privilege of swimming through the vaults beneath the opera.

Exploring Close to the Edge Cave
"There was at best a vague plan. It was a true dirtbag trip"
The trip seemed simple enough when Neeld Messler proposed it. Drive north with a car packed full of caving equipment and push the deepest pit in Canada past its 836-foot depth.
The trip was epic, my first true expedition. Equal amounts exhilarating and terrifying.
Follow the link in my bio for the whole adventure. 
Blog>Close to the Edge

Earlier this month, Dustin Mater (@dustign) and I had the honor of presenting our Mural of America work at the @insidenatgeo Storytellers Summit in LA  The project leverages the power of stories told on the landscape to reframe American History to include the first 20,000 years of human habitation of the Americas. Thanks @insidenatgeo @kaityarnall @vincentjmusi for having us out to talk about this work which has just began. Our aim is to have 10 interactive VR experiences completed by 2026. Thanks also to all of our fabulous co-presenters. Your work is an inspiration.

Follow the link in the nonprofit @ancientartarchive bio to learn more about the Mural of America, sign up for our mailing list and to support our work.

I've always had a fascination with the underground world. At first, I was obsessed with being one of the few people who could go into a cave. As my career progressed what caves preserve began to be more important. The underground world can act as a time capsule holding artwork made by people long before us. Those ancient artists are sending us messages from the past. My friend @dustign calls them "love notes in a bottle" from our ancestors. 
Those artists in the past are speaking to us if we let them. They are not just telling us who they were, they are telling us who we all are.

Happy New Year! My hope for this new year is that we all realize there is much more that connects us than divides us. Ancient images prove that point to me.
If one image could sum up all of humanity it would be the hand print. I have photographed them on every continent and across the time span of human history. This one is 36,000 years old from El Castillo in Spain. What the person who made this one meant by placing their hand on a cave wall and blowing pigment around it is lost to time, but how can you look at this image and not feel a connection to them?
For more follow the link in my profile AlvarezPhotography.Com>Blog>Human Hand Print

This week marks the 7th anniversary of the Bears Ears National Monument! It is the first National Monument to be established at the request of a coalition of Native American Tribes. It is also the first to be managed in partnership of the Tribes and the Federal Government. 
Bears Ears serves as a model of cultural resource management that can be applied to other public lands.

This literally saved my life (and grades) in uni!! ‚¨áÔ∏è‚úÖüíØüë©üèº‚Äçüéì
-
The Issue üò≠: 
There‚Äôs SO MUCH more content to learn in uni than compared to high-school üìö
Furthermore, lecturers are often experts in their field, with years and years of experience, and when they get excited about what they‚Äôre teaching, they may go way way overboard, and share more than you need to know for your exams.

The Solution ‚ú®: 
Focus on high-yield content. This is the content that will get you the most marks on your exam & assignments, and thus is the best use of your time.

You can find this through the learning objectives (usually at the start of each lecture or in your study guide) or by doing practice exams (as often the same questions/topics are repeated). üìù

An effective method I used was to turn each dot-point in the learning objectives into a question, then look through the lecture slides and other materials to answer the question, rather than reading every single page in the textbook or slides. ‚úÖ‚úÖ
-

The Hack: Cut your meetings 5-10min short, and use this time to send out a follow up email with actions! üìß 

Let‚Äôs face it. 
Most meetings go for longer than they should. By making your meetings shorter, you‚Äôll be forced to get to the point, and more likely to keep people‚Äôs attention, already improving the productiveness of the meeting (and gaining you brownie points with your coworkers for giving them time back) ü§ùüèΩ
¬†
But the real money-step of this hack comes from the follow up email. By sending this out IMMEDIATELY, you‚Äôre more likely to capture all the important points and it gives your coworkers more time to start working on what they were delegated. üèÜ‚è∞
¬†
In this email include:
üìß Summary of what was discussed
üìß Decisions made
üìß Next steps (and for each next step, WHO is responsible for, and WHEN it should be completed by)

The most IMPORTANT step in exam revision ‚úÖüíØüß†üë©üèº‚Äçüéì
-
WHAT IS TIMED PRACTICE? ‚è∞ 
This is where you do practice exams under full exam conditions (eg without notes, complete silence, reading time if applicable and no breaks).

This is a MUST do when preparing for exams because: 
üìï It helps you learn how to APPLY the knowledge. You could memorise the whole textbook and still do poorly on the exam if you don‚Äôt learn how to respond to questions the way examiners want you to. 
This is why so many students often complain that they get questions on the exams that they weren‚Äôt prepared for or have never seen before.
Exam questions often don‚Äôt ask you to just regurgitate definitions word for word, instead they will present a real world example (and likely a new one every time) to see if you can apply your knowledge to solve the problem! 
By doing practice questions and comparing your exams to the marking scheme, you will develop this skill quickly, and be prepared for ANY question you could get. 

üìï It helps you perfect your exam technique. By replicating the exam conditions, you will develop your own rhythm in terms of what you do during reading time, how long you spend on each questions, what you do for questions you don‚Äôt know etc. 
This is a skill itself, entirely seperate from knowing the content, that needs to be developed. 

üìï It giving you an idea of how much time you have & how quick you need to be!! Exams can be long, and being able to pace yourself and stay focused for the entire duration is something that also needs to be developed with practice. 
-

The sneakiest exam hack of all time! ‚úÖüß†üë©üèº‚ÄçüéìüíØ
-
The Hack: SPACED REPETITION üìÜ
This is a highly effective revision technique where you review content at regular, increasing intervals. 

For example: 
Say you learn something in class that day.
You would then review the content‚Ä¶ 
‚Äî> when you get home from school 
‚Äî> again that weekend 
‚Äî> the weekend after 
‚Äî> in a fortnight 
‚Äî> in a month 
‚Äî> in 3 months.

To take it one step further and make it even MORE effective, you should try to review using Active Recall, especially Practice Questions (eg from the textbook, past year papers). 

This will help you start perfecting your exam technique EARLY, help you commit the information to long-term memory, and understand the content on a deeper level.

So that when it comes to exam season, you won‚Äôt even NEED to revise because you‚Äôll know everything!! ‚úÖüèÜüíØ

These are ESSENTIAL to succeed in the workplace üíªüíØüìàüë©üèº‚Äçüíº
-
1Ô∏è‚É£ Be willing to give everything a go üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è- if you haven‚Äôt done it before or unsure, don‚Äôt be scared to ask for help! Tell your supervisor that you‚Äôll give it your best shot, but may need to be supervised or taught. 

A ‚Äúcan-do‚Äù attitude and an eagerness to learn is one of the best qualities to have. I constantly remind myself that I grow the most when I‚Äôm pushed out of my comfort zone, so the feeling of discomfort is actually something that I need to embrace. 

NOTE: this only refers to things that are inside the scope of your role & will help you develop. Be more cautious about saying yes to ‚Äúbusy work‚Äù just because your supervisor doesn‚Äôt want to do it.
.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Close the Loop üîÅ- at the end of every meeting or conversation, report back what you understood as actions you need to do & by when. Then, as you complete those actions, report back to inform the person they are done & any other information that might be useful (eg if doing research, what the main findings were. If reaching out to someone, what their response was).

Similarly, if you need help with something/are stuck, or there is something blocking your progress, let them know too (eg ‚Äúthe contact is away on leave and will be back Monday, which is when I will follow up again‚Äù).

Don‚Äôt wait for them to have to chase you to figure out that the task has been done or has been held up.

Closing the loop helps build trust. It lets your supervisor know that you are reliable and they can delegate important tasks to you. 
-

Getting Straight As is way easier than you think ‚¨áÔ∏è‚úÖüíØüë©üèΩ‚Äçüéì
-
HOW TO STUDY EFFECTIVELY üèÜ:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Use Active Study Methods - these are study methods that force you to engage with the content, doing some sort of physical or mental process. ü§ì 

It leads to greater retention of info, understanding, and ability to apply theory! 
It also means that you can learn SO MUCH MORE in MUCH LESS time. ‚úÖ
.
Examples include:
üß† Active Recall (e.g. Flashcards, Blurting, Application Questions)
üß† Mind-Maps & Drawing Diagrams 
üß† Teaching The Material to Others 
üß† Loci Method 
üß† Practice Exams 
.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Eliminate Distractions & Stay Focused - make sure you‚Äôre thinking only about the work in front of you to maximise retention. My favourite ways to do this are:
üíØ Study Timelapse 
üíØ Lofi-Beats & noise cancelling headphones 
üíØ Quiet, low-stimulus environment (e.g. library, dedicated study room) 
üíØ Chew gum (it actually works!)
üíØ App Blockers/Downtime settings on your phone 
.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Plan Your Sessions - by planning your study sessions out before you start, you will be able to prioritise what needs to be done, stay on track, and even get additional benefits without more time studying!
.
To make sure your study session is the best it can be: 
‚è∞ Use time-blocking (allocate a set amount of time for each activity, to create a sense of urgency. Otherwise it will expand to fill the whole time)
‚è∞ Start with a quick-win (easy subject or small homework task)to get the dopamine flowing; then move onto your most challenging topic whilst energy levels & focus is still high 
‚è∞ Interleave your subjects by studying smaller blocks of multiple subjects rather than 1 big block of one subject (e.g. 1 hour each of Math, Science, English rather than 3 hours of Math). This will help you remember MORE and perform better on exams, as proven by research üëèüèΩ 
-

.

Still thinking about my visit to their new DTLA space. After 6 visits to the OG west side Kato (and two unique pandemic takeouts!), I was beyond thrilled for the team to take their talents to the Row DTLA, allowing them to be bigger and better than ever. The BYOB has been replaced by an absolutely phenomenal bar program with innovative cocktails and an unbelievable wine list. The dishes have never been better, this current menu is without a doubt my favorite they‚Äôve ever created. the uni donut with jamon, the A5 wagyu, the caviar with geoduck and spinach (!)‚Ä¶ MAN! üò± The service has always been a standout, but like everything else they‚Äôve leveled that up too.

Congrats to @jonyao @dogsaget and the rest of the crew on the move. Y‚Äôall are a blessing.

Do yourself a favor. First, follow @breakfast_dreams. Then, keep an eye out for his schedule. Make plans. Circle the day on your calendar. Then wait patiently until that day comes and you can wrap your hands around the breakfast sandwich of your dreams.

Watching the assembly of these sandwiches was like watching an artist at work. The delicate way the cheese was placed on the SIXTY MINUTE sous vide egg. And can we talk about the bacon? Because we were all definitely talking about the bacon. Cap it off with his homemade fermented Calabrian Chile hot sauce and you have got a day that‚Äôs just been made.

Sometimes, you might even get lucky and stumble upon them doing a collab, like they did today with @aglscraftmeats. It was‚Ä¶ heaven. One of those times you really have to live in the moment knowing this is a one time thing.

In all seriousness, it was truly awesome to finally meet @liljoshygram and try his cooking after being #InternetFriends for so long. It was just extra special that the food was so damn good.

While I‚Äôm letting this pre-workout kick in, here‚Äôs a photo dump of the best food I ate in the last 30 days, my own cooking not included!

4. Discovered I live a few blocks from some amazing Thai fusion food. Been craving the Heavent Scent extra spicy from @spiceseasonstudiocity ever since.

7. Finally, @burgershewrote__. LA gets yet another smash burger, no I‚Äôm not mad about it.

Photo Dump: Highlights From Things I‚Äôve Eaten In The Last 6 Weeks.

I‚Äôll admit, sometimes I struggle quite a bit. Life ain‚Äôt easy, and sometimes it feels harder than it might be, and round these parts we accept that mental health should be a priority despite not doing enough to make it so.

A little blip of light between therapy appointments. üòú

Sometimes a work lunch is a protein bar. But sometimes work lunch is a phenomenal meal at @angeliniosteria. Those times are clearly better.

Work, suffice to say, did not suck today. One of the best Italian restaurants in a city full of them.

LA is truly becoming the food capitol of the country. And when you‚Äôve got Carolina style sauce as an option? üòÖ Congrats to the whole team. Looking forward to trying the pulled pork, the turkey and of course the beef ribs.

It‚Äôs a damn shame that in 2021, technology hasn‚Äôt advanced enough for me to get @bettinapizzeria delivered from Santa Barbara to LA. The first words out of my mouth after I took my first bite were, ‚ÄúWhat pizza is better than this? Seriously.‚Äù Ever since I had it, when I crave pizza‚Äî I crave Bettina. And that‚Äôs a problem.

meine Gedanken zum heutigen Thema: 
Das h√∂rt sich f√ºr viele vielleicht komisch an, aber der Name ,,Stefanie Giesinger‚Äò‚Äò hat ein Eigenleben entwickelt. Irgendwie ist es mein Name, aber irgendwie auch nicht‚Ä¶. mehr‚Ä¶schwer zu erkl√§ren.
Ich frage mich, ob das daran liegt, dass mein Name zu einer eigenst√§ndigen Marke wurde?

Heute geht es um Selbstvermarktung -
Sicherlich ein spannendes Thema f√ºr viele, vor Allem in einer Zeit in der jede f√ºnfte Person aus der GenZ sagt: Traumberuf Content Creator.

Alles berufliche mache ich intuitiv, mit meiner Freundin Leni und seit 3 Monaten wuchs die two-women show mit Julia. Ansonsten ist kein Management, keine PR oder andere Partei involviert.
Eine Strategie verfolgen wir f√ºr meine Karriere nicht, wir handeln nach bestem Wissen und Gewissen. Ideen f√ºr neue Projekte kommen immer sehr organisch. 
Mich interessiert es jedoch sehr, wie es andere erfolgreiche Frauen machen,wie sie ihre Karriere aufbauen und welche Tipps sie f√ºr euch und mich haben. 
Deswegen habe ich uns eine Expertin in Sachen Selbstvermarktung und Brandbuilding eingeladen‚Ä¶ @dagibee üíó

Ist es euer Traum Content creator zu werden?

Als Kind wollte ich Modedesignerin werden (schon seitdem ich denken kann, liebe ich Mode, vor allem faszinieren mich die Gef√ºhle, die Kleidungsst√ºcke in mir ausl√∂sen. Jedes Teil bringt etwas anderes in mir hervor und verleiht mir eine gewisse St√§rke. Denn dadurch kann ich entscheiden, wie ich von Anderen wahrgenommen werde.) Dann wollte ich Psychologin werden, denn die Gespr√§che, die ich mit den Psychologinnen f√ºhrte, zeigten mir immer, welch emphatische und intelligente Frauen sie sind. Ich wollte sein wie sie. Dann wusste ich, ich werde Model. Ohne dieses Ziel zu hinterfragen, verfolgte ich es und inzwischen stelle ich mir die Frage: wieso eigentlich? Ich glaube, es liegt an der Sichtbarkeit der Frauen in diesen Berufen. Sie sind f√ºr mich pr√§sent und von der Gesellschaft zelebriert. Vor allem Models beeindruckten mich: Ich wollte so Stark, Selbstst√§ndig, Selbstbewusst, Wohlhabend und geliebt sein wie die Frauen, die ich t√§glich in Magazinen, im Fernsehen und anderen Medien wahrnehmen konnte. Eins ist klar, ein junges Gehirn wird stark davon gepr√§gt, wie es sozialisiert wird. Und das bleibt nat√ºrlich auch im Erwachsenenalter so, unsere Au√üenwelt formt uns. Also habe ich mir die Frage nach meinen M√∂glichkeiten so beantwortet, dass gewisse Machtpositionen nur M√§nnern zustehen. Inzwischen stelle ich mir auch eine andere Frage, die mit meiner Identit√§t als Frau zusammenh√§ngt: Ich habe seit meiner Geburt eine Krankheit, eine Malrotation des Darms. Ich habe damals viel Zeit im Krankenhaus verbracht, meinen Symptomen wurden kein Glauben geschenkt. Es ist erschreckend, dass ich fast sterben musste, bis meine Krankheit diagnostiziert wurde. Die Folgen dieser Erfahrung sp√ºre ich bis heute. Ich frage mich also:‚Ä¶ W√§re es anders gelaufen, wenn ich ein Junge gewesen w√§re ? Denn abgesehen davon, dass M√§dchen weniger geglaubt wird, ist die Ungleichbehandlung von Frauen weiterhin Teil unserer Realit√§t. √Ñrzt*innen wurden prim√§r am m√§nnlichen K√∂rper ausgebildet, genauso wie viele Studien auf M√§nnern basieren, denn M√§nnlichkeit wurde als Norm definiert. In der heutigen Folge bei @g.spot.podcast Spreche ich dr√ºber wie viel Raum uns Frauen in unserer Gesellschaft geboten wird.

Things that happen in bed... ü´¶ You spend more time in bed than you think, so why not transform your bed into a tranquil oasis? These are some of the tips that could help you achieve that.
‚Ä¢ Quality Bedding. Invest in high-quality, comfortable sheets that are soft and breathable. My favorite ones are bamboo lyocell sheets from @cariloha‚Äôs Retreat Collection.
‚Ä¢ Aesthetics. Choose calming, neutral colors for your bedding, like white or ivory. Avoid printed sheets to create a serene atmosphere.
‚Ä¢ Pillows. Use memory foam pillows for added comfort, especially if you are struggling with neck pain.
‚Ä¢ Mattress Topper. Enhance the comfort of your mattress with a high-quality mattress topper that will provide extra cushioning.
‚Ä¢ Dim Lighting. Warm-toned light bulbs help to create a cozy and calming atmosphere.
‚Ä¢ Blackout Curtains. These can help block out morning light when you want to sleep in and create a more peaceful sleep environment.
‚Ä¢ Aromatherapy. As for scented candles, pick the ones with calming fragrances like lavender, chamomile, or eucalyptus.
‚Ä¢ Humidifier. It will help with your skin dryness and improve the quality of your sleep as you‚Äôll start breathing more freely.
‚Ä¢ Soft Rugs. Stepping onto a cushiony surface in the morning is a grounding experience that will help start the day on a positive note.
‚Ä¢ Electronic Devices. Limit phone usage before bedtime as the blue light radiated from screens can interfere with your sleep.

The truth about ALMOND CROISSANTSü•ê

Croissants go stale so quickly!! So here‚Äôs what you can do when you have a few extra ones laying around :) Or if you don‚Äôt want to pay the almond croissant premium LOL.

‚ú®Ingredients:
‚Ä¢1 cup water
‚Ä¢1/3 cup sugar

‚Ä¢4 croissants
‚Ä¢25 gr unsalted butter
‚Ä¢60 gr cane sugar
‚Ä¢60 gr almond flour
‚Ä¢1 medium egg
‚Ä¢1 tsp vanilla extract
‚Ä¢sliced almonds
‚Ä¢powder sugar for dusting

In a small saucepan, bring water and 1/3 cup of sugar to a boil to make a syrup. Cool down. Preheat oven 350¬∞F and cut croissants in half. In a bowl, combine softened unsalted butter with sugar. Then add almond flour, combine, and lastly add egg and vanilla to form an almost paste. Brush sugar syrup on the inside and outside of the croissant and then spread the almond paste inside. Close the croissant and spread more paste on top and top off with sliced almonds. Bake for 15-18 mins, cool down, and dust with powdered sugar. Enjoy!

EASY SPICY TUNA POKE BOWLSüêüü•£üå∂Ô∏è (full recipe below)

I think spicy tuna bowls are the new hot girl meal. I know raw fish can be a little intimidating, so make sure you buy previously flash-frozen fish from a grocer that you trust! I buy my ahi tuna filets from @Sprouts and eat them the day of.

‚ú®Ingredients (4 servings) // about 60gr protein per portion 

-1 1/2 lbs raw ahi tuna (2 steaks)
-1 1/2 tbsp sriracha
-2-3 tbsp aminos or soy sauce
-3 tbsp Kewpie mayonnaise
-1 cup edamame
-1 hass avocado
-1 cup uncooked sushi rice
-1 tbsp mirin
-1 tbsp rice vinegar
-1/2 tbsp sesame oil
-1 tsp salt
-1 tsp sesame seeds

Pat dry ahi tuna and cut it into 1-inch cubes. Place inside a bowl and add sriracha, aminos, and mayo. Stir until combined, cover, and rest refrigerated for at least 15 minutes. Cook sushi rice according to the instructions on the package. Warm up frozen edamame by pouring boiling water on top and letting it sit for 5 minutes. Slice avocado or mash it; feel free to season it however you like. Add mirin, rice vinegar, sesame oil, and salt to cooked rice. Stir and use it as a base for your bowl. Continue plating by adding about 4 ounces of tuna, 1/4 cup of edamame, and 1/4-1/2 an avocado. Portions are up to you! Top with sesame seeds, and feel free to add any extra sauce and seasonings like furikake. Enjoy immediately and save any leftovers in a tight-lid container in the fridge. Eat the same day.

Leading Australian architecture and design practice Gray Puksand has converted a heritage warehouse in Sydney‚Äôs CBD into a creative studio.
 
A series of internal arches reference how the building was once three buildings, now combined. Other reminders of an earlier era include a narrow horse cartway to the back courtyard now occupied by three popular small bars that enliven Sydney‚Äôs hidden ‚Äòcreative precinct‚Äô.

Built in 1935, St Stephen‚Äôs Uniting Church was designed in the interwar Gothic style by architects John Reid and Finlay Munro junior.
 
The church features Australian materials and work by local craftspeople and designers, including timber panelling in polished Queensland maple, plaster ceilings inspired by the English Perpendicular Gothic style, and leadlight windows by the prolific artist Norman St Clair Carter.
 
Visitors at Sydney Open will be able to walk around the building and get up close to the stained-glass windows designed by Carter.
 
Learn more through the link in our bio https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/st-stephens-uniting-church/
 
#SydneyOpen2023
 
Photo ¬© Kerry Myers

Australian at heart, with international studios and a global outlook, BVN embraces advancements in technology and makes space for the exploration of new ideas.
 
BVN designed its workspace and design studio to be immersive, with 3D printing robots, model makers, a VR (virtual reality) space and design workshop areas.
 
This Sunday, experience immersive VR with the BVN visualisation team and join BVN model maker Barry Cantor at the model-making station for kids. Learn mor through the link in our bio
 
https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/bvn-architecture-sydney-studio/
 
#SydneyOpen2023 @bvnarchitecture 
 
Photo ¬© Josh Robenstone

The Garrison Church, is a unique heritage-listed complex that is also one of the earliest extant ecclesiastical buildings in the state, and the hall is considered a rare and unique surviving example of a parochial school built in the 1840s.
 
The Gothic Revival church and hall were completed in stages between 1840 and 1878. Architect Henry Ginn designed the first stage of the church building, which was constructed from locally quarried sandstone and completed in 1846.
 
Explore the Garrison‚Äôs unique history and architectural beauty on a tour led by members of the church community at Sydney Open. Link in our bio
https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/garrison-church/
 
#SydneyOpen2023 @churchhillsyd 
 
Photo ¬© Joseph Koh courtesy of the Garrison Church

Can you believe we are just five days out from Sydney Open?!
 
Be sure to visit our Plan Your Day page on the Sydney Open website. Get access to the Sydney Open digital map, plan your talk and tour times, use one of our pre-planned trails to optimise your walking routes, and check out the variety of food and beverages options you will have access to at Sydney Open.
 
Link in our bio https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/plan-your-day/
 
#SydneyOpen2023

The Nightingale Building ‚Äì today known as the Nightingale Wing of Sydney Hospital ‚Äì was the site of the first nursing school in Australia. On the request of colonial politician Henry Parkes, British nurse Florence Nightingale sent Lucy Osburn and five other nurses to NSW to establish the school of nursing.
 
Architect Thomas Rowe designed the sandstone and polychrome-brick Gothic Revival building with Nightingale‚Äôs input.
 
Visitors on Sydney Open will see the Lucy Osburn-Nightingale Museum, which has a collection of medical equipment, records, implements and pathology that provides a look into the history of nursing and medicine in Australia from 1788.
 
Learn more about the Nightingale Wing through the link in our bio https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/nightingale-wing-sydney-hospital/
 
#SydneyOpen2023
 
Photo ¬© Katrina James for MHNSW

Built for funeral trains running between Sydney and the Rookwood Necropolis, Mortuary Station is the only surviving example of purpose-built Victorian railway funerary architecture in Australia.
 
Opened in 1869, Mortuary Station was the terminus for a funeral train service that transported the deceased, mourners, clergymen and visitors to Rookwood Cemetery.
 
Join the hourly tours at Sydney Open as a Transport for NSW heritage specialist talks about the history of Mortuary Station and the site.‚ÄØ
 
https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/mortuary-station/

The other day was my day for the ‚Äúdreaded Glucose test‚Äù that typically happens between week 24-28 of pregnancy. I went an alternative route during my pregnancy with Rell so I never experienced the glucola drink, BUT this time my doctor offered a natural alternative to the standard glucose drink, called the Fresh Test. (I have no affiliation with this) It ended up not being so ‚Äúdreaded‚Äù of an experience after all.
It still creates that glucose load with 50g of sugar, but it tastes like a refreshing lemonade and it‚Äôs non-gmo, with no additives and preservatives, and I didn‚Äôt feel icky at all. (It does warn that some may experience side effects‚Äî that is a lot of sugar at once!) I was even able to eat a boiled egg before my test as mine was a non-fasting test, but of course follow what your provider suggests! I mixed the powder with some water and drank it an hour before my blood draw. The visit to the lab was easy. And now I just wait for my results! üôèüôè
__
I wanted to share this quick experience and just bring awareness that there is a natural alternative that you can explore with your doctor when it‚Äôs time for your Glucose Test during pregnancy. Obviously this is an important step for mama and baby during pregnancy, so this is up to you and your doctor, but I personally love learning about other alternatives that feel right to me.

SAVE this for a quick Egg Free Breakfast option!
Rell has never liked eggs- never. Which led us to exploring if there was something instinctual behind it and we learned she had an egg allergy when she was a baby. The great news is, she can eat eggs baked into things, and I think she‚Äôs growing out of this allergy BUT she still dislikes eggs. Obviously eggs are an easy and awesome way for quick protein for breakfast‚Äî especially in the form of egg bites! SO it was time to explore a new Quick Protein option for breakfast and she LOVES these Sausage bites! We call them ‚Äúmuffins‚Äù üòâ Wether you‚Äôre catering to an egg allergy in your home or not- this is a great breakfast alternative to keep in your fridge or freezer for when you need a quick and healthy breakfast grab!
*I make these gluten free- and they can easily be made dairy free!
‚Äî
RECIPE
-1lb ground Breakfast Sausage
-1-2 cups finely chopped broccoli florets (optional, but a great way to add greens into breakfast!)
-1 cup your choice of gluten free flour (I used Bob‚Äôs Red Mill Paleo All Purpose mix)
-1 tsp baking powder
-1 cup shredded cheese- I use goat cheddar. You can simply make this dairy free with a dairy free cheese alternative!
-3/4 cup Almond Milk (or your choice of milk)
‚Äî
‚Ä¢Saut√© 1 lb breakfast sausage & finely chopped broccoli florets in avocado oil until sausage is fully cooked 
‚Ä¢In a mixing bowl, add 1 cup gluten free flour, 
1 tsp baking powder, & mix together. 
‚Ä¢Then add 1 cup shredded cheese. Mix all together.
‚Ä¢Add and mix in cooked sausage & broccoli to the dry mix. 
‚Ä¢Add 3/4 cup of Almond Milk. Mix together well.
‚Ä¢Scoop mixture into pre-greased cupcake pan- I use avocado oil spray. 
‚Ä¢Bake for 20-25 minutes at 400 degrees.

Enjoy these!! You can store in the fridge for a few days, or freeze them for when needed! Approved by my toddler‚Äî and my husband and I love them too!

#eggfreebreakfast #glutenfree #toddlerbreakfast #glutenfreebreakfast

A MUST on your weekly meal rotation! SAVE for this delicious Sausage, Kale, Ravioli soup. This was inspired by another recipe I saw via Instagram, but I made some upgrades to make it Gluten Free and healthier! We use a Grain Free Ravioli- but you can use a gluten free ravioli/tortellini, or any type of Gluten Free Pasta! I suggest a simple pasta if you‚Äôre wanting to make this Dairy Free.
Oh, and obviously, wait til it‚Äôs cooled down to eat‚Äî I basically burned my mouth in the making of this reel!üòÇ
__
Ingredients
-1¬†lb Spicy or Mild Italian chicken Sausage‚Äî I buy this from the meat counter at the grocery store. 
-1¬†small yellow onion,¬†diced
-5-7¬†cloves¬†garlic,¬†minced
-3¬†Tbsp Gluten Free¬†flour (I use Bob‚Äôs Red Mill Paleo all purpose flour mix)
-1¬†tsp¬†dried basil
-¬Ω¬†tsp¬†dried oregano
-a pinch of cayenne (omit if you‚Äôre trying to keep the spice level low)
-1¬†tsp (gluten free) hot sauce (I use Sweet Baby Ray‚Äôs hot sauce- equivalent to Franks)
-¬Ω¬†tspmustard powder
-1¬†cup¬†full fat Coconut Milk (I prefer it canned)
-32 oz Chicken Broth (I used Kettle & Fire)
-2-3 cups¬†organic kale,¬†chopped
-1 Box of @cappellos Grain Free Ravioli (I find this in the freezer section, and try to thaw for a bit before cooking) OR use your choice of gfree pasta or gluten free tortellini!

üòû This is difficult for me to write. Last week I stepped outside my comfort zone and shared a very personal goal of mine to have my book make the New York Times Best Seller list. üò± The list isn‚Äôt released until this Sunday but my editor at NatGeo said publishers find out a few days early and she would call me right away. I got the call. She shared the sad news that I didn‚Äôt make the list. üòî I kept it together on the call..but the tears came hard as soon as we said bye. I‚Äôm surprised I care so much about this. I cried for about 5 minutes and after a great pep talk from a supportive husband was able to pick myself up. ü•π

üíõ I want to make it clear that above all, I‚Äôm extremely proud of my book and don‚Äôt want this to cast any sort of shadow over the past 4 years that were nothing but a positive experience of writing and creating this treasure for families all around the world. üåé The quality of my hard work is definitely more important than the accolade of New York Times Best Seller. But I think, if I were to try my best to explain why I‚Äôm feeling so sad and even slightly embarrassed it‚Äôs because 2 things: I‚Äôve never wanted anything like this for myself. I‚Äôm sure so many other mothers out there can relate. I endlessly cheer and support my family, but rarely do I want something so purely for myself. This was that for me. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Secondly, the Bucket List community has rallied so hard behind me. I have have felt it every day of this journey. I was excited to celebrate this achievement all of us together. ‚ù§Ô∏èüíôüíö You‚Äôve done so much for me. Thx to you, we‚Äôve surpassed NatGeo‚Äôs presale records. I‚Äôm going to keep my head up and focus on the positive. There‚Äôs still chance I may make the list in future weeks so I‚Äôll keep trying my best. Positive reviews of my book on Amazon and Goodreads help so much. ‚≠êÔ∏è I want you to know that I screenshot your thoughtful reviews and every time you share my book on Instagram in such cute creative ways and add it to a journal I‚Äôve been keeping of this book publishing journey. Thank you for being a part of my story and all the ups and downs. This day is a down for me. But I know I can get back up..‚ù§Ô∏è Jess

To prepare stuffing, add all ingredients in a bowl & mix until well combined.

Once stuffing has cooled, use fingers to gently stuff each zucchini. 

In a large fry pan, melt 2 tbsp ghee. Fry the zucchini, turning frequently, in batches until they just change colour. Return all the zucchini to pan & cover with just enough water. Bring to a gentle boil & leave to simmer for 20 min. (Place a heat proof plate on the zucchini to keep them submerged). 

At 20 min the zucchini should have softened. Remove from water & set aside. Do not discard the cooking water. Strain it & set aside. (There should be about 2 cups of liquid, if less top it up with more water to make 2 cups).

‚Ä¢ 1-2 cups of water

Then boil room temperature eggs for 7 minutes, and then remove and cool in an ice bath.

If Jesus. That‚Äôs the title of a series of teachings I‚Äôve been doing at our church this January. If Jesus is here ‚Äî if Jesus is good ‚Äî if Jesus is Lord ‚Äì then that changes everything. Those three ideas are like a three-legged stool. If any one of those concepts is missing (or even cut a little short), our entire idea and belief in who Jesus is will simply topple over. We need each of these three attributes to be complete and strong if we‚Äôre to grow in our understanding of the true Jesus. And if we do, it changes everything ‚Äî our outlook on life and its challenges, our decisions, our relationships, our purpose, and eventually our eternity.

Which of these three attributes of Jesus do you think are most misunderstood or missing in our lives: his presence, his goodness, or his authority and power as Lord? Take the poll and drop in your thoughts.

‚ÄúFurniture‚Ä¶ lots of furniture!‚Äù @klekktic 

The Matrix is one of my all time favourite movies. It came out 25 years ago, inspiring a whole generation of filmmakers, visual effects artists and stunt coordinators. 

This is my take on the iconic ‚Äúguns, lots of guns‚Äù scene where Neo & Trinity enter The Matrix to prepare for battle. I thought this would be a fun and innovative way of showcasing a furniture brand. Having different products from the @klekktic collection flying into the Matrix. 

To execute this @shravanraoo & I shot for a full 12 hours in a studio in Dubai. Heba, the founder of Klekktic, who plays Trinity in this video, helped coordinate all of the Klekktic pieces to be shipped to the studio. We then placed each item one by one filming the product and then removing it. This allowed us to create the effect of different pieces flying into place.

@Klekktic is a beautiful UAE based brand. They have a minimal design aesthetic that is clean and elegant. The best part about their products is they are customizable. For example, the desk at the start of the video I fully customized from a dining room table into an office desk with draws and storage. Bed sizes, table lengths, mirror finishings etc can all be customized to fit your space size and preference. 

My home project is really starting to take shape. It‚Äôs been a long time coming but it‚Äôs been worth the wait. More coming on that soon‚Ä¶

Special shout out to @shravanraoo who helped me film this and then worked on the kick ass visual effects. 

What do you guys think of the video? Drop a Matrix reference comment below if you liked the video!

#TheMatrix #Klekktic #Dubai #Furniture #interior #UAE #Matrix #InteriorDesign

Showing you the world of @MarinaHomeInteriors 

I love challenging myself, and for this video I wanted to get creative by making a travel inspired piece of content but all from the Marina Home showroom in Dubai.

Travel is a huge part of my life, so when I learnt about the inspiration and international origins of Marina Home‚Äôs furniture it got me excited about making something fun that would highlight those countries and cultures. In this video there are 9 countries that are represented. Indonesia, Holland, France, Turkey, The UK, India, China, The US and Italy. Have a guess and drop a comment as to which is which. 

Setting up a new home is a very personal experience. Product choices and recommendations can come with lots of different opinions. That‚Äôs why I thought it would be fun to have ‚Äúmultiple Tom‚Äôs‚Äù in this video. Each Tom advising the other Tom on what furniture I should choose. There are so many different looks and vibes which makes it difficult as all the @MarinaHomeInteriors furniture is awesome! 

Bonus points for anyone who picked up on the Messi vrs Ronaldo chess scene. As soon as I saw that set up in the showroom I knew I had to bring out my inner football fan. 

From places to spaces we love, creating with @MarinaHomeInteriors has been a lot of fun. I hope you feel we‚Äôve been able to transform Marina Home‚Äôs showroom into a series of captivating travel destinations. Highlighting the rich diversity of their product offering as I traverse across various countries and cultures. Who‚Äôs interested in immersing themselves in the world of Marina Home?

Special shout out to @bramhansel who helped me make this. In a single day we spent 9 hours at the Showroom with over 50+ outfit changes!

What do you know about Venezuela? üáªüá™ 

Back in July I had the opportunity to spend a few weeks in Venezuela creating something special for @beautifuldestinations. 

As 2023 has been the year of AI, I‚Äôve been wanting to innovate and figure out a way to combine new immersive AI visuals with travel content. My thinking was that we‚Äôd be going to a place that not many people have seen before, Angel Falls in Canaima National Park, and if we could combine never before seen AI content with a truly out of this world destination then we‚Äôd have all the ingredients for something special. 

The first person I called was @andras.ra who‚Äôs been diving into short form AI content this year. We‚Äôve worked together a ton over the years and he‚Äôs an editing magician. The idea developed into a FPV Drone only concept where we‚Äôd play with generative AI to add little details into the video. @reme_martyr then joined the team to execute the aerials, he killed it! As the concept got bigger so did the team with @alexislefrene , @shravanraoo , @andres.visual and @bahaamalaeb joining the squad. 

What started as a fun idea turned into a full blown innovation project, looking to create the world‚Äôs first AI supported Tourism Campaign. By tapping into unique visual styles the hope was to create something that would make some noise and spark a conversation about the destination.

What you wouldn‚Äôt know is that 40 years ago my parents lived in Venezuela. At that time, Caracas was a global advertising hub. Ironically, my Dad was working in the same field that I am now. Back then he was one of the few photographers paving the way through dark room visual effects, that‚Äôs before photoshop existed! It was very cool to be there 40 years later trying to do something similar, as Venezuela announces itself as a new and exciting Tourism destination. I love the country‚Äôs new branding ‚Äúopen to the future‚Äù and I hope this video gives you a glimpse of that future as well as the future of content and where I think it‚Äôs going. 

This video is quite the rollercoaster so fasten your seat belt and enjoy the ride‚Ä¶

Back to the future with @tomjauncey 

Imagine time traveling from 1971 to 2071. That‚Äôs the idea behind this iPhone only video for @visit.dubai 

‚ÄúI wanted to create something fun in Dubai that would throw us back to the 70s. It‚Äôs a period of time that is so influential in today‚Äôs mainstream music and fashion worlds. To create that authentic feel I teamed up with Dubai based fashion designer @dianamuza_ to customize a handmade 70s outfit with all the materials and accessories coming from Deira. For the music I worked with internationally renowned DJ & Producer, @guest_cuts , to digitally remaster a vinyl track from the 70s to give the video that feel good disco vibe.

I love coming up with original ideas and doing things a little different. As the UAE was founded in 1971 I thought it would be fun to take a trip to the future! The challenge was to create something unique, shot only on iPhone, that would juxtapose a retro vibe with a futuristic setting. Puppies & Pilates üêïü¶æ

For the last month I‚Äôve been doing Pilates with the awesome Gaby Noble founder of @exhalepilateslondon, as a way to improve my strength training. Prior to this year I had no idea what Pilates was and always thought of it as a workout for women. I couldn‚Äôt have been more wrong. 

As I wait for Project Apartment to get fully underway I‚Äôve turned my empty home into a Pilates Studio. This is just one of the many brutal exercises that are getting me lifting heavier than I ever have and feeling more recovered each day. 

There‚Äôs a big reason why a lot of elite male athletes, celebrities and performers have added Pilates to their training regimes üëáüèΩ

- Improves your muscle to mind connection. I am so focused on the movements and getting the muscles to do exactly what it needs to do. Something I never think about when weightlifting. 

- Improves core strength. Killer ab workout every single time!

- Helps me lift more, squat deeper, recover quicker, lets the joints and muscles breathe. This is why it‚Äôs been the perfect supplement to my strength training. 

- Limits injuries so I can keep pushing towards my goals without set backs. My flexibility and mobility has completely changed in 1 month. Again, allowing me to lift heavier, get stronger and recover faster. 

- Improves your posture & helps keep a healthy spine. Both are key for the work I do and ultimately make me move better and with more ease.

This is just the start of my Pilates journey but I‚Äôve been loving it so far with Gaby Noble @exhalepilateslondon . If you‚Äôre interested in trying it out shoot her a message. She‚Äôs the best in the space and trained the likes of Harry Styles, Kate Moss, Giancarlo Esposito & Christian Eriksen. 

How many of you guys have done Pilates?
